r (Non-Classical)]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"[[Let's Get Serious (song)|Let's Get Serious]]\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"|Best Rhythm & Blues Song\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[25th Annual Grammy Awards|1983]]\n| \"[[That Girl (Stevie Wonder song)|That Girl]]\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|\"[[Do I Do]]\"\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| Best R&B Vocal Performance, Male\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental and Vocals|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocal(s)]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|\"[[Ebony and Ivory]]\"\n| Record of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"[[Tug of War (Paul McCartney album)#Track listing|What's That You're Doing]]\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[27th Annual Grammy Awards|1985]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|\"[[I Just Called to Say I Love You]]\"\n| Song of the Year\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| Best Pop Vocal Performance, Male\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| \"[[I Just Called to Say I Love You|I Just Called To Say I Love You (Instrumental)]]\"\n| Best Pop Instrumental Performance\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| ''[[The Woman in Red (soundtrack)|The Woman In Red]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Best R&B Vocal Performance, Male\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[28th Annual Grammy Awards|1986]]\n| ''[[In Square Circle]]''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n| \"[[Part-Time Lover]]\"\n| Best Pop Vocal Performance, Male\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[29th Annual Grammy Awards|1987]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|\"[[That's What Friends Are For#Dionne Warwick cover|That's What Friends Are For]]\"\n| Best Pop Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Record of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[30th Annual Grammy Awards|1988]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|\"[[Skeletons (Stevie Wonder song)|Skeletons]]\"\n| Best Rhythm & Blues Song\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|Best R&B Vocal Performance, Male\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[31st Annual Grammy Awards|1989]]\n| ''[[Characters (Stevie Wonder album)|Characters]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[34th Annual Grammy Awards|1992]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|\"[[Gotta Have You (Stevie Wonder song)|Gotta Have You]]\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written Specifically for a Motion Picture or for Television]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"Jungle Fever\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[38th Annual Grammy Awards|1996]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|\"[[For Your Love (Stevie Wonder song)|For Your Love]]\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Male R&B Vocal Performance|Best Male R&B Vocal Performance]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Rhythm & Blues Song\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[39th Annual Grammy Awards|1997]]\n| \"[[The Adventures of Pinocchio (1996 film)#Soundtrack|Kiss Lonely Goodbye (Harmonica with Orchestra)]]\"\n| Best Pop Instrumental Performance\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[40th Annual Grammy Awards|1998]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|\"[[How Come, How Long]]\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Short Form Music Video]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals|Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[41st Annual Grammy Awards|1999]]\n| \"How Come, How Long\" (Live)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|\"St. Louis Blues\"\n| Best Male R&B Vocal Performance\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocal(s)\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[45th Annual Grammy Awards|2003]]\n| \"Love's In Need Of Love Today\"\n| Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| \"Christmas Song\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"|Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[47th Annual Grammy Awards|2005]]\n| \"Moon River\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"|[[48th Annual Grammy Awards|2006]]\n| \"A Time To Love\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| ''[[A Time to Love (album)|A Time To Love]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Album|Best R&B Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"[[So What the Fuss]]\"\n| Best Male R&B Vocal Performance\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"How Will I Know\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"So Amazing\"\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| \"[[From the Bottom of My Heart (Stevie Wonder song)|From The Bottom Of My Heart]]\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Male Pop Vocal Performance|Best Male Pop Vocal Performance]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[49th Annual Grammy Awards|2007]]\n| \"[[For Once in My Life]]\"\n| Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[51st Annual Grammy Awards|2009]]\n| \"Never Give You Up\"\n| Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[52nd Annual Grammy Awards|2010]]\n| \"[[All About the Love Again]]\"\n| Best Male Pop Vocal Performance\n| {{nom}}\n{{end}}\n\n=== Other awards and recognition ===\nWonder has been given a range of awards for his music, and for his civil rights work, including induction into the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame|Songwriters]] and the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame|Rock and Roll]] halls of fame; gaining a Lifetime Achievement Award from the [[National Civil Rights Museum]], being named one of the [[United Nations Messengers of Peace]], and earning a [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] from President [[Barack Obama]] in 2014.\n\nIn December 2016, the [[Detroit|City of Detroit]] recognized Wonder's legacy by renaming a portion of his childhood street, Milwaukee Avenue West, between Woodward Avenue and Brush Street, as \"Stevie Wonder Avenue\". He was also awarded an honorary key to the city, presented by Mayor [[Mike Duggan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/12/21/stevie-wonder-avenue-unveiling-ceremony-detroit/95697552/|title=Isn't it lovely? Stevie Wonder gets a street in Detroit|first=Brian |last=McCollum|work=Detroit Free Press|date=December 22, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=May 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"min-width:60em\"\n! Awards and recognition\n|-\n|\n* Star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]\n* 1983: inducted to the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]].<ref name=SongwritersHallOfFame/>\n* 1984: received an [[Academy Award for Best Song]] for \"[[I Just Called to Say I Love You]]\" from the movie ''[[The Woman in Red (1984 film)|The Woman in Red]]''.<ref name=AcademyAwards/>\n* 1989: inducted to the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]].<ref name=RockHallOfFame/>\n* 1999: received the [[Polar Music Prize]]<ref name=PolarMusic/> and [[Kennedy Center Honors]].<ref>[//www.kennedy-center.org/programs/specialevents/honors/history/home.html The Kennedy Center \u2013 Past Honorees]. Retrieved on October 11, 2008.</ref>\n* 2002: received the [[UCLA Spring Sing#The George and Ira Gershwin Award|George and Ira Gershwin Lifetime Achievement Award]] at UCLA's [[UCLA Spring Sing|Spring Sing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uclalumni.net/calendarevents/springsing/Gershwin/winners.cfm |title=Gershwin Award Winners |accessdate=October 12, 2008 |work=UCLAlumni.net |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817021611/http://www.uclalumni.net/calendarevents/springsing/Gershwin/winners.cfm |archivedate=August 17, 2011 }}</ref> The same year, Wonder received the [[Sammy Cahn]] Lifetime Achievement Award from the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/ceremony/awards/C3003 |title=Sammy Cahn Lifetime Achievement Award |accessdate=October 30, 2008 |work=Songwriter's Hall of Fame |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014103654/http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/ceremony/awards/C3003 |archive-date=October 14, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* 2004: received the [[Billboard Century Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/yearend/2006/century/2004.jsp |title=Stevie Wonder Billboard's 2004 Century Award Honoree |accessdate=October 12, 2008|first= Gail |last= Mitchell |work=Billboard |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080510024830/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/yearend/2006/century/2004.jsp |archivedate = May 10, 2008}}</ref> Also in 2004, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked him No. 15 on their list of the [//www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5939214/the_immortals_the_first_fifty/ 100 Greatest Rock and Roll Artists of All Time].<ref>{{cite web| title = The Immortals: The First Fifty| work = Rolling Stone| issue=946|publisher = | url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5939214/the_immortals_the_first_fifty}}</ref>\n* 2006: was inducted, as one of the first inductees, into the [[Michigan Walk of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.michiganwalkoffame.com/news_details.asp?nid=61 |title=MI Walk of Fame Announces First Inductees |accessdate=October 12, 2008 |date=March 14, 2006 |work=Michigan Walk of Fame |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071029124822/http://www.michiganwalkoffame.com/news_details.asp?nid=61 |archivedate=October 29, 2007  }}</ref> The same year, Wonder received a Lifetime Achievement Award from the [[National Civil Rights Museum]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soulshine.ca/news/newsarticle.php?nid=3828 |title=Stevie Wonder Gets Lifetime Achievement Award |accessdate=October 21, 2008 |date=October 20, 2006|work=Soulshine}}</ref>\n* 2008: Ranked at number five on \"The Billboard Hot 100 Top All-Time Artists\", making him as the third most successful male artist in the history of [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/specials/hot100/charts/top100-artists-20.shtml |title=Billboard Hot 100 Chart 50th Anniversary |work=Billboard| accessdate=October 1, 2009}}</ref>\n* February 23, 2009: Recipient of the Library of Congress's second [[Gershwin Prize]] For Popular Song, honored by US President Barack Obama at the [[White House]].<ref name=\"Wonder receives prize\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7909915.stm |title=Wonder receives award |work=BBC News |date=February 26, 2009 |accessdate=February 27, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/09/02/AR2008090202702.html |title=Stevie Wonder to Receive Gershwin Prize for Song |accessdate=December 13, 2008 |date=September 3, 2008|work=Washington Post | first=J. Freedom |last= du Lac}}</ref>\n* 2009: Recipient of the [[Montreal Jazz Festival]] Spirit Award.<ref name=SpiritAward/> This special award underlines a popular artist's extraordinary contribution to the musical world. The Montreal Jazz Festival Spirit Award is in bronze.\n* 2009: Named a [[United Nations Messengers of Peace|Messenger of Peace]] by the United Nations.<ref name=\"un.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=33118&Cr=disable&Cr1=|title=Singer-songwriter Stevie Wonder designated UN Messenger of Peace|date=December 1, 2009|publisher=United Nations|accessdate=April 27, 2010}}</ref>\n* March 6, 2010: Wonder was appointed a Commander of the [[Order of Arts and Letters]] by French Culture Minister [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Mitterrand]]. Wonder had been due to be invested with this honor in 1981, but scheduling problems prevented this from happening. A lifetime achievement award was also given to Wonder on the same day, at France's biggest music awards.<ref name=\"Wonder lifetime achievement\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8553585.stm |title=Stevie Wonder receives top French honour |work=BBC News |date=March 7, 2010 |accessdate=March 7, 2010}}</ref>\n* June 2011: the [[Apollo Theater]] inducted Wonder into the Apollo Legends Hall of Fame.<ref>Allen, Floyd (February 4, 2011), [https://archive.today/20120709021900/http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/108732/20110204/stevie-wonder-apollo-legends-hall-of-fame-apollo-theater-wonder-child.htm \"Stevie Wonder joins list of Apollo Legends Hall of Fame recipients\"]. ''[http://au.ibtimes.com International Business Times AU]''. Retrieved February 4, 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite news| last=Feeney| first= Michael J. |url= http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/uptown/stevie-inducted-apollo-theater-hall-fame-star-studded-celebration-harlem-article-1.132414 |title= Stevie Wonder inducted into Apollo Theater hall of fame with star-studded celebration in Harlem| newspaper= [[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] | date= June 17, 2011| accessdate= July 22, 2015}}</ref>\n* 2013: received the Music Makes One Global Ambassador Award from the outstanding music award ceremony of Asia and the World, [[2013 Mnet Asian Music Awards|Mnet Asian Music Awards]].<ref>[//mama.interest.me/history?type=winner&year=2013 \"2013 M.net Korean Music Festival Winners list\"]. ''MAMA''. Retrieved December 14, 2014.</ref>\n* 2014: Recipient of the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2014/11/10/president-obama-announces-presidential-medal-freedom-recipients |title=President Obama Announces the Presidential Medal of Freedom Recipients |accessdate=November 11, 2014 |date=November 10, 2014|work=The White House}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Honorary degrees===\nStevie Wonder has received many [[honorary degree]]s in recognition of his music career. These include:\n\n{| border=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%; margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; border:1px #056 solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">State</span><!--Can be changed to country once foreign degrees are included--> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Date</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:40%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">School</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Degree</span>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Alabama}} || '''June 2, 1996''' || [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]] || [[Doctor of Music]] (D.Mus.)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/factbook/sections/15-16_FactsFigures2017_HonoraryDegrees.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=December 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213082011/https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/factbook/sections/15-16_FactsFigures2017_HonoraryDegrees.pdf |archive-date=December 13, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Connecticut}} || '''May 22, 2017''' || [[Yale University]] || [[Doctor of Music]] (D.Mus.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courant.com/education/hc-yale-commencement-20170521-story.html|title=Yale Honors Stevie Wonder, John Kerry, John Lewis At Commencement|first=Kathleen|last=Megan|publisher=}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n{{Expand list|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Stevie Wonder discography}}\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* ''[[The Jazz Soul of Little Stevie]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[Tribute to Uncle Ray]]'' (1962)\n* ''[[With a Song in My Heart (Stevie Wonder album)|With a Song in My Heart]]'' (1963)\n* ''[[Stevie at the Beach]]'' (1964)\n* ''[[Up-Tight]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[Down to Earth (Stevie Wonder album)|Down to Earth]]'' (1966)\n* ''[[I Was Made to Love Her (album)|I Was Made to Love Her]]'' (1967)\n* ''[[Someday at Christmas]]'' (1967)\n* ''[[Eivets Rednow]]'' (1968)\n* ''[[For Once in My Life (Stevie Wonder album)|For Once in My Life]]'' (1968)\n* ''[[My Cherie Amour (album)|My Cherie Amour]]'' (1969)\n* ''[[Signed, Sealed & Delivered]]'' (1970)\n* ''[[Where I'm Coming From]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[Music of My Mind]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Talking Book]]'' (1972)\n* ''[[Innervisions]]'' (1973)\n* ''[[Fulfillingness' First Finale]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Songs in the Key of Life]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Stevie Wonder's Journey Through \"The Secret Life of Plants\"]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Hotter than July]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[The Woman in Red (soundtrack)|The Woman in Red]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[In Square Circle]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Characters (Stevie Wonder album)|Characters]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Jungle Fever (soundtrack)|Jungle Fever]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Conversation Peace]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[A Time to Love (album)|A Time to Love]]'' (2005)\n}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n{{Wikipedia books|Stevie Wonder}}\n* [[Harry Mendell]], who collaborated musically with Stevie Wonder on two albums\n* [[List of Billboard Hot 100 chart achievements and milestones|List of ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart achievements and milestones]]\n* [[List of artists who reached number one on the Hot 100 (U.S.)]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons|Stevie Wonder}}\n* {{official website}}\n* {{Britannica|647209}}\n* {{discogs artist}}\n* {{IMDb name|0005567}}\n* {{NYTtopic|people/w/stevie_wonder}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Stevie Wonder}}\n*[http://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/stevie-wonder Stevie Wonder Interview] NAMM Oral History Library (2016)\n\n{{Stevie Wonder}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Stevie Wonder\n|list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestOriginalSong 1981\u20131990}}\n{{Gershwin Prize}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song}}\n{{Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Original Song}}\n{{Grammy Award for Album of the Year 1970s}}\n{{Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Non-Classical}}\n{{Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award}}\n{{Kennedy Center Honorees 1990s}}\n{{MusiCares Person of the Year}}\n{{Polar Music Prize}}\n{{1989 Rock and Roll Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wonder, Stevie}}\n[[Category:Stevie Wonder]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American keyboardists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:African-American composers]]\n[[Category:African-American male composers]]\n[[Category:African-American songwriters]]\n[[Category:American songwriters]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n[[Category:Activists for African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:American child singers]]\n[[Category:American tenors]]\n[[Category:American harmonica 