{"title_page": "Jonathan Gruber (economist)", "text_new": "{{Infobox economist\n|name              = Jon Gruber\n|image             = Jonathan Gruber at US House Oversight Cmte in 2014.jpg\n|birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1965|9|30}}\n|birth_place       = \n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|alma_mater        = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])}}<br>[[Harvard University]] {{small|([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n|institution       = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]\n|field             = [[Health economics]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Lawrence F. Katz]]<ref>[http://search.proquest.com/docview/304000122 Changes in the structure of employer-provided health insurance]</ref>\n|doctoral_students = [[Susan Dynarski]]<ref>Dynarski, Susan (1999), ''[https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/9517 Student aid and college attendance: analysis of government intervention in the higher education]''. Ph.D. dissertation, Massachusetts Institute of Technology.</ref> <br>[[Amy Finkelstein]]<ref>Finkelstein, Amy (2001), ''[https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/8652 Adverse selection and government intervention in life and health insurance markets]''. Ph.D. dissertation, Massachusetts Institute of Technology.</ref><br>[[Melissa Kearney]]<br>[[Ebonya Washington]]<ref>Washington, Ebonya  (2003), ''[https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/17633 Essays in public finance]''. Ph.D. dissertation, Massachusetts Institute of Technology.</ref>\n|repec_prefix      = e\n|repec_id          = pgr20\n}}\n'''Jonathan Holmes Gruber''' (born September 30, 1965) is an American professor of economics at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], where he has taught since 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://economics.mit.edu/faculty/gruberj|title= Jonathan Gruber|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= MIT Economics| publisher= |accessdate=December 16, 2014}}</ref> He is also the director of the Health Care Program at the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]], where he is a research associate. An associate editor of both the ''Journal of Public Economics'' and the ''[[Journal of Health Economics]]'', Gruber has been heavily involved in crafting [[public health policy]].\n\nHe has been described as a key architect<ref name=\"everything you wanted to know\">{{cite news |title=Everything you wanted to know about health reform, in one comic book |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/post/everything-you-wanted-to-know-about-health-reform-in-one-comic-book/2011/10/11/gIQAN4AzcL_blog.html |work=Wonkblog |publisher =The Washington Post |first=Sarah |last=Kliff |date=October 11, 2011}}</ref> of both the 2006 [[Massachusetts health care reform]], sometimes referred to as \"Romneycare\", and the 2010 [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], sometimes referred to as the \"ACA\" and \"Obamacare\". He became the focus of a media and political firestorm in late 2014 when videos surfaced in which he made controversial statements about the legislative process, marketing strategies, and public perception surrounding the passage of the ACA.\n\n==Early life==\nGruber was born on September 30, 1965, the son of Martin Jay Gruber and Ellie Gruber. His father is Professor Emeritus of Finance at the [[New York University Stern School of Business]], having taught there for more than 40 years. Jonathan Gruber was raised in the New York suburb of [[Ridgewood, New Jersey]]. He completed his [[Bachelor of Science|BS]] in [[economics]] from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in 1987 and his [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in economics from [[Harvard University]] in 1992, with a thesis titled ''Changes in the Structure of Employer-Provided Health Insurance''.<ref>{{cite book|date=1992|title=Changes in the structure of employer-provided health insurance|first=Jonathan|last=Gruber|id={{ProQuest|304000122}}}}</ref> He has 3 children. Rachel Gruber, Jack Gruber, and Ava Gruber.\n\n==Academic research career==\nGruber began his career as an assistant professor of economics at MIT in 1992.<ref name=\"economics.mit.edu\">{{cite web| url=http://economics.mit.edu/files/9877| accessdate=July 25, 2014|title=Gruber MIT bio}}</ref>{{Better source needed|date=March 2020}} He is also a research associate at the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]].<ref name=\"economics.mit.edu\"/>{{Better source needed|date=March 2020}} Gruber's research has focused on public finance and health economics.\n\n==Government work and consulting==\nDuring the 1997\u201398 academic year, Gruber was on leave as Deputy Assistant Secretary for Economic Policy at the [[United States Department of the Treasury]].\n\n===Massachusetts health care reform===\nFrom 2003-06 he was one of the architects of [[Massachusetts health care reform]], also known as \"Romneycare.\"<ref name=\"a thank you\">{{cite news|title=Viewpoint: A thank you to Gov. Mitt Romney for signing Massachusetts' historic health care reform|url=http://www.masslive.com/opinion/index.ssf/2012/04/viewpoint_a_thank_you_to_gov_m.html|first=Jonathan|last=Gruber|work=[[The Republican (Springfield, Massachusetts)|The Republican]]|date=April 11, 2012}}</ref>  In 2006 he became an inaugural member of the Health Connector Board, the main implementing body for that effort. \n\nGruber was ousted from the Massachusetts Health Connector in February 2015.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sarah|last=Wheaton|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/02/jonathan-gruber-massachusetts-obamacare-115523.html|title=Jonathan Gruber among 4 ousted from Massachusetts Obamacare board|date=February 25, 2015|work=Politico}}</ref>\n\n===Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act===\nDuring the 2008 election he was a consultant to the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]], [[John Edwards|Edwards]] and [[Barack Obama|Obama]] presidential campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leighbureau.com/speakers/JGruber|title=Looking at the National Health Care Debate through a Massachusetts Lens|last=Groves|first=Victoria|date=May 2, 2011|website=[[Harvard Kennedy School]]|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> \n\nFrom 2009-10, Gruber served as a technical consultant to the Obama Administration and worked with both the administration and [[U.S. Congress]] to help craft the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], often referred to as the ACA or \"Obamacare\". The Act was signed into law in March 2010, and Gruber has been described as an \"architect\", \"writer\", and \"consultant\" of the legislation. He was widely interviewed and quoted during the legislation's roll-out.<ref>{{cite news|first=Catherine|last=Rampell|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/29/business/jonathan-gruber-health-cares-mr-mandate.html?pagewanted=all|title=Academic Built Case for Mandate in Health Care Law|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> \n\n===Vermont health care reform===\nIn 2010 and 2011, Gruber was involved in crafting and advocating for the [[Vermont health care reform|Single-Payer and Unified Health System]] bill in [[Vermont]], which passed in May 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obamacare Architect To Help Vermont Design Single Payer|url=http://digital.vpr.net/post/obamacare-architect-help-vermont-design-single-payer|first=Peter|last=Hirschfield|work=[[Vermont Public Radio]]|date=July 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"proposal\">[http://www.leg.state.vt.us/jfo/healthcare/Hsiao%20Proposal%20-%20public.pdf \"The Vermont Option: Achieving Affordable Universal Health Care\"], William Hsaio, Steven Kappel, Jonathan Gruber, and a team of health policy analysts, June 21, 2010.</ref>\n\nThe bill established Green Mountain Care, which aimed to be the first-ever state-level [[single-payer health care]] system in the United States by the time it was to have kicked in fully in 2017. Green Mountain Care was cancelled in December 2014 by Governor [[Peter Shumlin]] saying its projected costs were becoming too high.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/governor-abandons-single-payer-health-care-plan-225042240.html \"Governor abandons single-payer health care plan\"], yahoo.com, December 17, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nGruber has published more than 140 research articles (the majority of which were for NBER) and has edited six research volumes.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.nber.org/authors/jonathan_gruber|author=Jonathan Gruber|journal=National Bureau of Economic Research|title=NBER Working Papers by Jonathan Gruber|accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe is a co-editor of the ''Journal of Public Economics'', an associate editor of the ''Journal of Health Economics'', and the author of ''Public Finance and Public Policy''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bcs.worthpublishers.com/gruber3e/#t_544924____|title=Worth Publishers Student Center for Public Finance and Policy|publisher=Bcs.worthpublishers.com|accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref> In 2011, he wrote ''Health Care Reform: What It Is, Why It's Necessary, How It Works'', delineating the Affordable Care Act, and illustrated by Nathan Schreiber.<ref name=\"everything you wanted to know\"/>\n\nGruber's published works include:\n* In 1999, the ''[[Quarterly Journal of Economics]]'' published \"Abortion legalization and child living circumstances: who is the 'marginal child'?\"<ref name=\"QJE2\">{{cite journal |last=Gruber |first=J. |last2=Levine |first2=P. |last3=Staiger |first3=D. |title=Abortion Legalization and Child Living Circumstances: Who is the \"Marginal Child\"? |journal=Quarterly Journal of Economics |year=1999 |volume=114 |issue=1 |pages=263\u201391 |doi=10.1162/003355399556007 |citeseerx=10.1.1.493.8996 }}</ref> which suggests that the legalized abortion has a selective effect for reducing the birth of \"marginal children\" that saved the government over $14 billion in welfare payments through 1994.\n* Writing for the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]] in 2002, Gruber worked together with [[Sendhil Mullainathan]] on a paper titled \u201cDo [[Cigarette taxes in the United States|Cigarette Taxes]] Make Smokers Happier\", which did find an improvement in smokers\u2019 psychological state because higher taxes were a disincentive to smoking.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Mullainathan|first1=Sendhil|last2=Gruber|first2=Jonathan |title=Do Cigarette Taxes Make Smokers Happier? |journal=NBER Working Paper No. 8872 |date=April 2002 |doi=10.3386/w8872 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n* On February 15, 2006, the [[Center on Budget and Policy Priorities]] published an article by Gruber entitled \"The Cost and Coverage Impact of the President's Health Insurance Budget Proposals\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.cbpp.org/2-15-06health.htm|journal=Center on Budget and Policy Priorities|title=The Cost and Coverage Impact of The President's Health Insurance Budget Proposals|date=February 15, 2006|accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref>\n* In a December 4, 2008 editorial in ''[[The New York Times]]'', \"Medicine for the Job Market\", he claimed that expanding health insurance, even in difficult financial times would stimulate the economy.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gruber|first=Jonathan|date=December 4, 2008|title=Medicine for the Job Market|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/04/opinion/04gruber.html}}</ref>\n* In an article for the National Institute for Health Care Management Foundation in April 2010, \"Taxing Sin to Modify Behavior and Raise Revenue\", Gruber advocated a sort of \"[[sin tax]]\" for the obese. He uses the model of [[Cigarette taxes in the United States|cigarette taxes]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nihcm.org/pdf/ExpertVoices_Gruber_April2010.pdf|title=Taxing Sin to Modify Behavior and Raise Revenue|date=April 2010|accessdate=February 7, 2015}}</ref>\n* On February 9, 2011, the [[Center for American Progress]] published an article by Gruber titled \"Health Care Reform Without the Individual Mandate\", analyzing the health insurance coverage impacts of alternative policy options for encouraging purchase of health insurance under the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], including the mandate, a late penalty, and automatic enrollment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.americanprogress.org/issues/2011/02/gruber_mandate.html|last=Gruber|first=Jonathan|date=February 9, 2011|title=Health Care Reform Without the Individual Mandate|work=American Progress|accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2006, Gruber received the American Society of Health Economists Inaugural Medal for the best health economist in the nation aged 40 and under.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://web.mit.edu/shass/soundings/issue_06f/honors.html|title=Honors & awards \u2013 Fall 2006 Soundings|publisher=Web.mit.edu|accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref> He was elected a member of the [[Institute of Medicine]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nasi.org/about/spotlight/jonathan-gruber|title=National Academy of Social Insurance|publisher=National Academy of Social Insurance|accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref> In 2009 he was elected to the Executive Committee of the [[American Economic Association]].{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nIn 2011 he was named \u201cOne of the Top 25 Most Innovative and Practical Thinkers of Our Time\u201d by ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' Magazine. In both 2006 and 2012 he was rated as one of the top 100 most powerful people in health care in the United States by ''Modern Healthcare'' Magazine.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\n==Controversies==\n===Non-disclosure of HHS contract===\nIn January 2010, after news emerged that Gruber was under a $297,000 contract with the [[U.S. Department of Health and Human Services]], while at the same time promoting the [[Obama administration]]'s [[health care reform]] policies, some commentators suggested a [[conflict of interest]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/01/08/economist-contract-health-department-touting-reform|title=Economist Was Under Contract With HHS While Touting Health Reform Bill| work=Fox News|date=January 8, 2010|accessdate=November 15, 2013|author=Berger, Judson}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Ronald|last=Brownstein|date=January 8, 2010|title=On Jonathan Gruber's Conflict Of Interest|website=[[The Atlantic]]|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2010/01/on-jonathan-grubers-conflict-of-interest/33215}}</ref> [[Paul Krugman]] in ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|first=Paul|last=Krugman|url=https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/01/11/jonathan-gruber|title=Jonathan Gruber|work=The New York Times|date=January 11, 2010|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> argued that, although Gruber didn't always disclose his HHS connections, the times when he didn't were no big deal. In response to Krugman's contention, ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'''s [[Glenn Greenwald]] wrote, \"What will make it impossible to effectively call out wrongdoing by future corrupt administrations (by which Krugman seems to mean: Republican administrations) is the willingness of some people to tolerate and defend corruption when done by 'their side.'\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Glenn|last=Greenwald|url= http://www.salon.com/2010/01/16/krugman_5|title=Krugman, Gruber and non-disclosure issues|publisher=Salon Media Group|date=January 16, 2010|accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Description of ACA subsidies===\nOne heavily scrutinized part of the ACA reads that subsidies should be given to healthcare recipients who are enrolled \"through an Exchange established by the State\". Some have read this to mean that subsidies can be given only in states that have chosen to create their own healthcare exchanges, and do not use the federal exchange, while the Obama administration says that the wording applies to all states. This dispute was part of a series of lawsuits referred to collectively as ''[[King v. Burwell]]''. In July 2014, two separate recordings of Gruber, both from January 2012, surfaced in which he seemed to contradict the administration's position. In one, Gruber states, in response to an audience question, that \"if you\u2019re a state and you don\u2019t set up an exchange, that means your citizens don't get their [[tax credits]]\",<ref>{{cite web|last=Radia|first=Ryan|title=Obamacare Architect Admitted in 2012 States without Exchanges Lose Subsidies|date=July 24, 2014|url=https://cei.org/blog/obamacare-architect-admitted-2012-states-without-exchanges-lose-subsidies|website=[[Competitive Enterprise Institute]]}}</ref> while in the other he says, \"if your governor doesn't set up an exchange, you're losing hundreds of millions of dollars of tax credits to be delivered to your citizens\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Serwer|first=Adam|title=Adviser's past remarks could give Obamacare a headache|date=July 26, 2014|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/jonathan-gruber-video-obamacare#53439|website=msnbc.com}}</ref> When these recordings emerged, Gruber called these statements mistaken, describing them as \"just a speak-o\u2014you know, like a typo\".<ref name=\"just a mistake\">{{cite news|title=Jonathan Gruber: 'It Was Just a Mistake'|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/118851/jonathan-gruber-halbig-says-quote-exchanges-was-mistake|work=The New Republic|first=Jonathan|last=Cohn|date=July 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===\"Grubergate\" videos controversy===\nIn November 2014, a series of videos emerged of Gruber speaking about the ACA at different events, from 2010 to 2013, in ways that proved to be controversial; the controversy became known in the press as \"Grubergate\".<ref>{{cite news|title='Grubergate' shows the sad state of debate on Obamacare|url=http://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-skocpol-obamacare-gruber-20141210-story.html|first=Theda|last=Skocpol|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> In the first, most widely publicized video, taken at a panel discussion about the ACA at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in October 2013, Gruber said the bill was deliberately written \"in a tortured way\" to disguise the fact that it creates a system by which \"healthy people pay in and sick people get money\". He said this obfuscation was needed due to \"the stupidity of the American voter\" in ensuring the bill's passage. Gruber said the bill's inherent \"lack of transparency is a huge political advantage\" in selling it.<ref name=\"YouTube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G790p0LcgbI|title=GRUBER: \"Lack of transparency is a huge political advantage\"|publisher=American Commitment|date=October 13, 2013|accessdate=November 10, 2014}}</ref> The comments caused significant controversy.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kathleen|last=Parker|date=November 12, 2014|title=Obama and the 'Stupidity of the American Voter|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=November 12, 2014|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/commentary/ct-barack-obama-affordable-care-act-stupidity-perspec-1113-jm-20141112-story.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=ACA Architect: 'The Stupidity Of The American Voter' Led Us To Hide Obamacare's True Costs From The Public |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/theapothecary/2014/11/10/aca-architect-the-stupidity-of-the-american-voter-led-us-to-hide-obamacares-tax-hikes-and-subsidies-from-the-public|work=Forbes|first=Avik|last=Roy|date=November 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Jose A.|last=DelReal|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2014/11/11/obamacare-consultant-under-fire-for-stupidity-of-the-american-voter-comment|title=Obamacare consultant under fire for 'stupidity of the American voter' comment|work=Washington Post|accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn two subsequent videos, Gruber was shown talking about the decision (which he attributed to [[John Kerry]]) to have the bill tax insurance companies instead of patients (the so-called \"Cadillac tax\"), which he called fundamentally the same thing economically but more palatable politically. In one video, he stated that \"the American people are too stupid to understand the difference\" between the two approaches, while in the other he said that the switch worked due to \"the lack of economic understanding of the American voter\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Obamacare: Voters, are you stupid?|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/11/14/politics/obamacare-voters-stupid-explainer|work=[[CNN]]|first=Jeremy|last=Diamond|date=November 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn another video, taken in 2010, Gruber expressed doubts that the ACA would significantly reduce health care costs, although he noted that lowering costs played a major part in the way the legislation had been promoted.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obamacare architect discussed misleading public in 4th newly uncovered video|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/11/13/politics/tapper-gruber|work=CNN|first=Jake|last=Tapper|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref> In another video, taken in 2011, Gruber again talks about manipulation behind the \"Cadillac tax\", this time also stating that the tax is designed so that, though it begins by affecting only 8% of insurance plans, it will \"over the next 20 years\" come to apply to nearly all employer-provided health plans.<ref name=\"obama promised\">{{cite news|title=Obama promised Obamacare wouldn't do exactly what Gruber says it will do|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/11/18/politics/gruber-obamacare-promises|work=[[CNN]]|first=Jake|last=Tapper|date=November 19, 2014}}</ref> Journalist [[Jake Tapper]] noted that Gruber's description of the \"Cadillac tax\" directly contradicted a promise that Obama had made before the bill was passed.<ref name=\"obama promised\"/>\n\nAfter the first of these videos came out, Gruber apologized and conceded he \"spoke inappropriately\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Jonathan Gruber to MSNBC: My 'Stupidity of the American Voter' Remark was Inappropriate|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/jonathan-gruber-to-msnbc-my-stupidity-of-the-american-voter-remark-was-inappropriate|work=Mediaite|first=Eddie|last=Scarry|date=November 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSome defenders of the ACA, such as [[Jonathan Cohn]], called Gruber's statements about Americans \"wrong and inappropriate\" while maintaining that the trickery of which Gruber spoke was standard procedure in passing legislation in Washington, D.C., and thus not a cause for scandal.<ref>{{cite news|title=What Jon Gruber's Quotes Really Tell Us About Obamacare\u2014and American Politics|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/120311/jonathan-gruber-and-obamacare-what-his-quotes-really-tell-us|first=Jonathan|last=Cohn|work=The New Republic|date=November 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Obamacare Debate Was One of the Most Transparent in Recent Memory|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/120251/jonathan-gruber-obamacare-comments-get-aca-history-wrong|first=Brian|last=Beutler|work= [[The New Republic]]|date=November 12, 2014}}</ref> Opponents of the Act, on the other hand, were harsher in their criticism: ''[[National Review|National Review Online]]'' editor and conservative commentator [[Rich Lowry]] said the videos were emblematic of \"the progressive mind, which values complexity over simplicity, favors indirect taxes and impositions on the American public so their costs can be hidden, and has a dim view of the average American\",<ref>{{cite news|title=Thank You, Jonathan Gruber|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/392672/thank-you-jonathan-gruber-rich-lowry|work=National Review|first=Rich|last=Lowry|date=November 14, 2014}}</ref> while commentator [[Charles Krauthammer]] called the first video \"the ultimate vindication of the charge that Obamacare was sold on a pack of lies.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The Gruber Confession|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/392644/gruber-confession-charles-krauthammer|work=National Review|first=Charles|last=Krauthammer|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nConservative [[S.E. Cupp]] wrote that the videos showed \"willful ignorance\" on Gruber's part in thinking that the Act was successfully marketed to voters, stating that \"the law has never cracked a 51% favorability rating\" and that, in the [[United States elections, 2010|first elections after the ACA passed]], Republicans, who had opposed it, retook the [[U.S. House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] and gained control of 11 additional state governorships.<ref>{{cite news|title=The guy who thinks voters are 'stupid'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/11/13/opinion/cupp-gruber-obamacare|first=S.E.|last=Cupp|work=CNN|date=November 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Nancy Pelosi]], then-Speaker of the House, who successfully shepherded the legislation through the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]], without a single GOP vote and despite some opposition from pro-life Democrats, stated in a press conference after the Gruber controversy, ''\"So I don't know who he is. He didn't help write our bill\"'', a comment [[PolitiFact]] described as \"inaccurate\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2014/nov/13/nancy-pelosi/nancy-pelosi-says-she-doesnt-know-who-jonathan-gru |title=Nancy Pelosi says she doesn't know who Jonathan Gruber is |website=PolitiFact.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Martosko |first=David |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2833632/Pelosi-disowns-Obamacare-architect-Jonathan-Gruber-stupidity-American-voter-video.html |title=Nancy Pelosi disowns Obamacare 'architect' Jonathan Gruber over video |website=Dailymail.co.uk |date=2014-11-13 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n====Congressional hearing====\nIn the wake of the controversy, Jonathan Gruber was called to testify before members of [[United States Congress]]. He gave testimony on December 9, 2014, in which he apologized for his remarks, which he called \"glib, thoughtless, and sometimes downright insulting\".<ref name=GruberTestimonyGowdyQuestion>{{cite AV media | people=Gruber, Jonathan| date=9 December 2014|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gnXzJm1sJRM| title=Rep. Trey Gowdy questions Jonathan Gruber (C SPAN) |location=Washington, DC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=MIT professor apologizes for health care law remarks|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2014/12/09/mit-professor-jonathan-gruber-apologizes-congress-for-remarks-about-stupidity-american-voter/AlrfLb2yWKWNTL9OvSaPFJ/story.html|work=Boston Globe|first=Noah|last=Bierman|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', in an editorial, called Gruber's apology unpersuasive, saying that \"his response to substantive questions suggested that he is mainly sorry for getting caught on tape\".<ref name=\"wallstreetjournal\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/forrest-gump-ph-d-1418171139|work= Wall Street Journal|title=Forrest Gump, PhD|date=December 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Effect on Vermont single-payer plan====\nOn December 17, 2014, [[Governor of Vermont|Vermont Governor]] [[Peter Shumlin]] cancelled the [[Vermont health care reform]] plan, on which Gruber had served as a consultant.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vermont bails on single-payer health care|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/12/vermont-peter-shumlin-single-payer-health-care-113653.html|first=Sarah|last=Wheaton|work=Politico|date=December 17, 2014}}</ref> Although budgetary concerns were cited as the reason for the cancellation, some called Gruber's involvement with the plan a factor as well.<ref>{{cite news |title=How Math, Lawsuits, and Jonathan Gruber Killed Vermont's Single-Payer Health Care Dream|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2014-12-18/how-math-lawsuits-and-jonathan-gruber-killed-vermonts-singlepayer-health-care-dream|first=David|last=Weigel|work=Bloomberg|date=December 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Vermont Public Radio|VPR]], Vermont state auditor Doug Hoffer is auditing Gruber's contracts<ref>{{cite news|title=Auditor: Invoices unsupported from Vt.health \"expert\"|url=http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/story/news/politics/2015/01/23/vt-deal-health-expert-gruber-scrutiny/22222125|first=Dave|last=Gram|work=[[Burlington Free Press]]|date=January 24, 2015}}</ref> for [[Vermont health care reform]], which Gruber \"helped Vermont design\".<ref>{{cite news|title=State's Contract With Economist Jonathan Gruber Under Scrutiny|url=http://digital.vpr.net/post/states-contract-economist-jonathan-gruber-under-scrutiny|first=Peter|last=Hirschfeld|work=VPR|date=January 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Extent of contributions===\nThe extent of Gruber's contributions to both Massachusetts and federal health care reform has been the source of significant controversy. In 2014, the Obama administration claimed that Gruber did not have a major role in creating the ACA.<ref name=\"SArmourWSJ06212015\">{{cite news|last=Armour|first=Stephanie|date=June 21, 2015|title=MIT Economist Jonathan Gruber Had Bigger Role in Health Law, Emails Show|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mit-economist-jonathan-gruber-had-bigger-role-in-health-law-emails-show-1434910195?KEYWORDS=Jonathan+Gruber|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]|location=[[New York City|New York]]|accessdate=June 22, 2015|quote=Jonathan Gruber, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology economist whose comments about the health-care law touched off a political furor, worked more closely than previously known with the White House and top federal officials to shape the law, previously unreleased emails show.}}</ref>\n\nAccording to emails released by the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|U.S. House Oversight Committee]] to ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', Gruber met and consulted with various Obama administration officials in charge of writing and developing the law,<ref name=\"SArmourWSJ06212015\"/> including [[Peter R. Orszag|Peter Orszag]], who was director of the [[Office of Management and Budget]] (OMB), [[Jason Furman]], an economic adviser to the president, [[Ezekiel Emanuel]], who was then a special adviser for health policy at OMB, [[Jeanne Lambrew]], a top Obama administration health adviser who worked at HHS and the White House, and [[Lawrence Summers]], then a top economic adviser in the administration.<ref name=\"SArmourWSJ06212015\"/> In July 2009, he was invited to meet personally with Obama.<ref name=\"SArmourWSJ06212015\"/>\n\nDuring his December 2014 congressional hearing, in both his written and oral testimony,<ref>{{cite news|title=Written Testimony of Professor Jonathan Gruber before the Committee on Oversight and Government Reform, U.S. House of Representatives|url=http://oversight.house.gov/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Gruber-Statement-12-9-ObamaCare1.pdf|work=United States Congress|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> Gruber downplayed his own influence on the Massachusetts and national health care plans, stating: \"I did not draft Governor Romney\u2019s health care plan, and I was not the 'architect' of President Obama\u2019s health care plan.\" The newspaper ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' called this a contradiction of various statements that Gruber had previously made, claiming that at \"numerous speeches, lectures and TV interviews in the past four years, Gruber has been introduced as the 'architect' of the Massachusetts law and/or Obamacare\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Gruber on ObamaCare: 'I helped write it'|url=http://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/226626-jonathan-gruber-on-obamacare-i-helped-write-it|first=Jesse|last=Byrnes|work=The Hill|date=December 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://economics.mit.edu/files/9877 CV of Jonathan Gruber]\n* [https://www.nber.org/authors/jonathan_gruber [[National Bureau of Economic Research]] Publications by Jonathan Gruber]\n* [http://econ-www.mit.edu/faculty/gruberj/ MIT Faculty Profile - Jonathan Gruber]\n\n{{Fellows of the Econometric Society elected in 2016}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gruber, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American economists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Econometric Society]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Health economists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox economist\n|name              = Jon Gruber\n|image             = Jonathan Gruber at US House Oversight Cmte in 2014.jpg\n|birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1965|9|30}}\n|birth_place       = \n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|alma_mater        = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])}}<br>[[Harvard University]] {{small|([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n|institution       = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]\n|field             = [[Health economics]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Lawrence F. Katz]]<ref>[http://search.proquest.com/docview/304000122 Changes in the structure of employer-provided health insurance]</ref>\n|doctoral_students = [[Susan Dynarski]]<ref>Dynarski, Susan (1999), ''[https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/9517 Student aid and college attendance: analysis of government intervention in the higher education]''. Ph.D. dissertation, Massachusetts Institute of Technology.</ref> <br>[[Amy Finkelstein]]<ref>Finkelstein, Amy (2001), ''[https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/8652 Adverse selection and government intervention in life and health insurance markets]''. Ph.D. dissertation, Massachusetts Institute of Technology.</ref><br>[[Melissa Kearney]]<br>[[Ebonya Washington]]<ref>Washington, Ebonya  (2003), ''[https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/17633 Essays in public finance]''. Ph.D. dissertation, Massachusetts Institute of Technology.</ref>\n|repec_prefix      = e\n|repec_id          = pgr20\n}}\n'''Jonathan Holmes Gruber''' (born September 30, 1965) is an American professor of economics at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], where he has taught since 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://economics.mit.edu/faculty/gruberj|title= Jonathan Gruber|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= MIT Economics| publisher= |accessdate=December 16, 2014}}</ref> He is also the director of the Health Care Program at the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]], where he is a research associate. An associate editor of both the ''Journal of Public Economics'' and the ''[[Journal of Health Economics]]'', Gruber has been heavily involved in crafting [[public health policy]].\n\nHe has been described as a key architect<ref name=\"everything you wanted to know\">{{cite news |title=Everything you wanted to know about health reform, in one comic book |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/post/everything-you-wanted-to-know-about-health-reform-in-one-comic-book/2011/10/11/gIQAN4AzcL_blog.html |work=Wonkblog |publisher =The Washington Post |first=Sarah |last=Kliff |date=October 11, 2011}}</ref> of both the 2006 [[Massachusetts health care reform]], sometimes referred to as \"Romneycare\", and the 2010 [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], sometimes referred to as the \"ACA\" and \"Obamacare\". He became the focus of a media and political firestorm in late 2014 when videos surfaced in which he made controversial statements about the legislative process, marketing strategies, and public perception surrounding the passage of the ACA.\n\n==Early life==\nGruber was born on September 30, 1965, the son of Martin Jay Gruber and Ellie Gruber. His father is Professor Emeritus of Finance at the [[New York University Stern School of Business]], having taught there for more than 40 years. Jonathan Gruber was raised in the New York suburb of [[Ridgewood, New Jersey]]. He completed his [[Bachelor of Science|BS]] in [[economics]] from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in 1987 and his [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in economics from [[Harvard University]] in 1992, with a thesis titled ''Changes in the Structure of Employer-Provided Health Insurance''.<ref>{{cite book|date=1992|title=Changes in the structure of employer-provided health insurance|first=Jonathan|last=Gruber|id={{ProQuest|304000122}}}}</ref> He has 3 children. Rachel Gruber, Jack Gruber, and Ava Gruber.\n\n==Academic research career==\nGruber began his career as an assistant professor of economics at MIT in 1992.<ref name=\"economics.mit.edu\">{{cite web| url=http://economics.mit.edu/files/9877| accessdate=July 25, 2014|title=Gruber MIT bio}}</ref>{{Better source needed|date=March 2020}} He is also a research associate at the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]].<ref name=\"economics.mit.edu\"/>{{Better source needed|date=March 2020}} Gruber's research has focused on public finance and health economics.\n\n==Government work and consulting==\nDuring the 1997\u201398 academic year, Gruber was on leave as Deputy Assistant Secretary for Economic Policy at the [[United States Department of the Treasury]].\n\n===Massachusetts health care reform===\nFrom 2003-06 he was one of the architects of [[Massachusetts health care reform]], also known as \"Romneycare.\"<ref name=\"a thank you\">{{cite news|title=Viewpoint: A thank you to Gov. Mitt Romney for signing Massachusetts' historic health care reform|url=http://www.masslive.com/opinion/index.ssf/2012/04/viewpoint_a_thank_you_to_gov_m.html|first=Jonathan|last=Gruber|work=[[The Republican (Springfield, Massachusetts)|The Republican]]|date=April 11, 2012}}</ref>  In 2006 he became an inaugural member of the Health Connector Board, the main implementing body for that effort. \n\nGruber was ousted from the Massachusetts Health Connector in February 2015.<ref>{{cite news|first=Sarah|last=Wheaton|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/02/jonathan-gruber-massachusetts-obamacare-115523.html|title=Jonathan Gruber among 4 ousted from Massachusetts Obamacare board|date=February 25, 2015|work=Politico}}</ref>\n\n===Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act===\nDuring the 2008 election he was a consultant to the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]], [[John Edwards|Edwards]] and [[Barack Obama|Obama]] presidential campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leighbureau.com/speakers/JGruber|title=Looking at the National Health Care Debate through a Massachusetts Lens|last=Groves|first=Victoria|date=May 2, 2011|website=[[Harvard Kennedy School]]|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> \n\nFrom 2009-10, Gruber served as a technical consultant to the Obama Administration and worked with both the administration and [[U.S. Congress]] to help craft the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], often referred to as the ACA or \"Obamacare\". The Act was signed into law in March 2010, and Gruber has been described as an \"architect\", \"writer\", and \"consultant\" of the legislation. He was widely interviewed and quoted during the legislation's roll-out.<ref>{{cite news|first=Catherine|last=Rampell|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/29/business/jonathan-gruber-health-cares-mr-mandate.html?pagewanted=all|title=Academic Built Case for Mandate in Health Care Law|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> \n\n===Vermont health care reform===\nIn 2010 and 2011, Gruber was involved in crafting and advocating for the [[Vermont health care reform|Single-Payer and Unified Health System]] bill in [[Vermont]], which passed in May 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obamacare Architect To Help Vermont Design Single Payer|url=http://digital.vpr.net/post/obamacare-architect-help-vermont-design-single-payer|first=Peter|last=Hirschfield|work=[[Vermont Public Radio]]|date=July 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"proposal\">[http://www.leg.state.vt.us/jfo/healthcare/Hsiao%20Proposal%20-%20public.pdf \"The Vermont Option: Achieving Affordable Universal Health Care\"], William Hsaio, Steven Kappel, Jonathan Gruber, and a team of health policy analysts, June 21, 2010.</ref>\n\nThe bill established Green Mountain Care, which aimed to be the first-ever state-level [[single-payer health care]] system in the United States by the time it was to have kicked in fully in 2017. Green Mountain Care was cancelled in December 2014 by Governor [[Peter Shumlin]] saying its projected costs were becoming too high.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/governor-abandons-single-payer-health-care-plan-225042240.html \"Governor abandons single-payer health care plan\"], yahoo.com, December 17, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nGruber has published more than 140 research articles (the majority of which were for NBER) and has edited six research volumes.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.nber.org/authors/jonathan_gruber|author=Jonathan Gruber|journal=National Bureau of Economic Research|title=NBER Working Papers by Jonathan Gruber|accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe is a co-editor of the ''Journal of Public Economics'', an associate editor of the ''Journal of Health Economics'', and the author of ''Public Finance and Public Policy''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bcs.worthpublishers.com/gruber3e/#t_544924____|title=Worth Publishers Student Center for Public Finance and Policy|publisher=Bcs.worthpublishers.com|accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref> In 2011, he wrote ''Health Care Reform: What It Is, Why It's Necessary, How It Works'', delineating the Affordable Care Act, and illustrated by Nathan Schreiber.<ref name=\"everything you wanted to know\"/>\n\nGruber's published works include:\n* In 1999, the ''[[Quarterly Journal of Economics]]'' published \"Abortion legalization and child living circumstances: who is the 'marginal child'?\"<ref name=\"QJE2\">{{cite journal |last=Gruber |first=J. |last2=Levine |first2=P. |last3=Staiger |first3=D. |title=Abortion Legalization and Child Living Circumstances: Who is the \"Marginal Child\"? |journal=Quarterly Journal of Economics |year=1999 |volume=114 |issue=1 |pages=263\u201391 |doi=10.1162/003355399556007 |citeseerx=10.1.1.493.8996 }}</ref> which suggests that the legalized abortion has a selective effect for reducing the birth of \"marginal children\" that saved the government over $14 billion in welfare payments through 1994.\n* Writing for the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]] in 2002, Gruber worked together with [[Sendhil Mullainathan]] on a paper titled \u201cDo [[Cigarette taxes in the United States|Cigarette Taxes]] Make Smokers Happier\", which did find an improvement in smokers\u2019 psychological state because higher taxes were a disincentive to smoking.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Mullainathan|first1=Sendhil|last2=Gruber|first2=Jonathan |title=Do Cigarette Taxes Make Smokers Happier? |journal=NBER Working Paper No. 8872 |date=April 2002 |doi=10.3386/w8872 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n* On February 15, 2006, the [[Center on Budget and Policy Priorities]] published an article by Gruber entitled \"The Cost and Coverage Impact of the President's Health Insurance Budget Proposals\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.cbpp.org/2-15-06health.htm|journal=Center on Budget and Policy Priorities|title=The Cost and Coverage Impact of The President's Health Insurance Budget Proposals|date=February 15, 2006|accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref>\n* In a December 4, 2008, ''[[New York Times]]'' op-ed, \"Medicine for the Job Market\", he claimed that expanding health insurance, even in difficult financial times would stimulate the economy.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gruber|first=Jonathan|date=December 4, 2008|title=Medicine for the Job Market|work=New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/04/opinion/04gruber.html}}</ref>\n* In an article for the National Institute for Health Care Management Foundation in April 2010, \"Taxing Sin to Modify Behavior and Raise Revenue\", Gruber advocated a sort of \"[[sin tax]]\" for the obese. He uses the model of [[Cigarette taxes in the United States|cigarette taxes]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nihcm.org/pdf/ExpertVoices_Gruber_April2010.pdf|title=Taxing Sin to Modify Behavior and Raise Revenue|date=April 2010|accessdate=February 7, 2015}}</ref>\n* On February 9, 2011, the [[Center for American Progress]] published an article by Gruber titled \"Health Care Reform Without the Individual Mandate\", analyzing the health insurance coverage impacts of alternative policy options for encouraging purchase of health insurance under the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], including the mandate, a late penalty, and automatic enrollment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.americanprogress.org/issues/2011/02/gruber_mandate.html|last=Gruber|first=Jonathan|date=February 9, 2011|title=Health Care Reform Without the Individual Mandate|work=American Progress|accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2006, Gruber received the American Society of Health Economists Inaugural Medal for the best health economist in the nation aged 40 and under.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://web.mit.edu/shass/soundings/issue_06f/honors.html|title=Honors & awards \u2013 Fall 2006 Soundings|publisher=Web.mit.edu|accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref> He was elected a member of the [[Institute of Medicine]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nasi.org/about/spotlight/jonathan-gruber|title=National Academy of Social Insurance|publisher=National Academy of Social Insurance|accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref> In 2009 he was elected to the Executive Committee of the [[American Economic Association]].{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nIn 2011 he was named \u201cOne of the Top 25 Most Innovative and Practical Thinkers of Our Time\u201d by ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' Magazine. In both 2006 and 2012 he was rated as one of the top 100 most powerful people in health care in the United States by ''Modern Healthcare'' Magazine.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\n==Controversies==\n===Non-disclosure of HHS contract===\nIn January 2010, after news emerged that Gruber was under a $297,000 contract with the [[U.S. Department of Health and Human Services]], while at the same time promoting the [[Obama administration]]'s [[health care reform]] policies, some commentators suggested a [[conflict of interest]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2010/01/08/economist-contract-health-department-touting-reform|title=Economist Was Under Contract With HHS While Touting Health Reform Bill| work=Fox News|date=January 8, 2010|accessdate=November 15, 2013|author=Berger, Judson}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Ronald|last=Brownstein|date=January 8, 2010|title=On Jonathan Gruber's Conflict Of Interest|website=[[The Atlantic]]|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2010/01/on-jonathan-grubers-conflict-of-interest/33215}}</ref> [[Paul Krugman]] in ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|first=Paul|last=Krugman|url=https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/01/11/jonathan-gruber|title=Jonathan Gruber|work=New York Times|date=January 11, 2010|accessdate=September 3, 2014}}</ref> argued that, although Gruber didn't always disclose his HHS connections, the times when he didn't were no big deal. In response to Krugman's contention, ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'''s [[Glenn Greenwald]] wrote, \"What will make it impossible to effectively call out wrongdoing by future corrupt administrations (by which Krugman seems to mean: Republican administrations) is the willingness of some people to tolerate and defend corruption when done by 'their side.'\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Glenn|last=Greenwald|url= http://www.salon.com/2010/01/16/krugman_5|title=Krugman, Gruber and non-disclosure issues|publisher=Salon Media Group|date=January 16, 2010|accessdate=February 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Description of ACA subsidies===\nOne heavily scrutinized part of the ACA reads that subsidies should be given to healthcare recipients who are enrolled \"through an Exchange established by the State\". Some have read this to mean that subsidies can be given only in states that have chosen to create their own healthcare exchanges, and do not use the federal exchange, while the Obama administration says that the wording applies to all states. This dispute was part of a series of lawsuits referred to collectively as ''[[King v. Burwell]]''. In July 2014, two separate recordings of Gruber, both from January 2012, surfaced in which he seemed to contradict the administration's position. In one, Gruber states, in response to an audience question, that \"if you\u2019re a state and you don\u2019t set up an exchange, that means your citizens don't get their [[tax credits]]\",<ref>{{cite web|last=Radia|first=Ryan|title=Obamacare Architect Admitted in 2012 States without Exchanges Lose Subsidies|date=July 24, 2014|url=https://cei.org/blog/obamacare-architect-admitted-2012-states-without-exchanges-lose-subsidies|website=[[Competitive Enterprise Institute]]}}</ref> while in the other he says, \"if your governor doesn't set up an exchange, you're losing hundreds of millions of dollars of tax credits to be delivered to your citizens\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Serwer|first=Adam|title=Adviser's past remarks could give Obamacare a headache|date=July 26, 2014|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/jonathan-gruber-video-obamacare#53439|website=msnbc.com}}</ref> When these recordings emerged, Gruber called these statements mistaken, describing them as \"just a speak-o\u2014you know, like a typo\".<ref name=\"just a mistake\">{{cite news|title=Jonathan Gruber: 'It Was Just a Mistake'|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/118851/jonathan-gruber-halbig-says-quote-exchanges-was-mistake|work=The New Republic|first=Jonathan|last=Cohn|date=July 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===\"Grubergate\" videos controversy===\nIn November 2014, a series of videos emerged of Gruber speaking about the ACA at different events, from 2010 to 2013, in ways that proved to be controversial; the controversy became known in the press as \"Grubergate\".<ref>{{cite news|title='Grubergate' shows the sad state of debate on Obamacare|url=http://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-skocpol-obamacare-gruber-20141210-story.html|first=Theda|last=Skocpol|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> In the first, most widely publicized video, taken at a panel discussion about the ACA at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in October 2013, Gruber said the bill was deliberately written \"in a tortured way\" to disguise the fact that it creates a system by which \"healthy people pay in and sick people get money\". He said this obfuscation was needed due to \"the stupidity of the American voter\" in ensuring the bill's passage. Gruber said the bill's inherent \"lack of transparency is a huge political advantage\" in selling it.<ref name=\"YouTube\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G790p0LcgbI|title=GRUBER: \"Lack of transparency is a huge political advantage\"|publisher=American Commitment|date=October 13, 2013|accessdate=November 10, 2014}}</ref> The comments caused significant controversy.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kathleen|last=Parker|date=November 12, 2014|title=Obama and the 'Stupidity of the American Voter|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=November 12, 2014|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/commentary/ct-barack-obama-affordable-care-act-stupidity-perspec-1113-jm-20141112-story.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=ACA Architect: 'The Stupidity Of The American Voter' Led Us To Hide Obamacare's True Costs From The Public |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/theapothecary/2014/11/10/aca-architect-the-stupidity-of-the-american-voter-led-us-to-hide-obamacares-tax-hikes-and-subsidies-from-the-public|work=Forbes|first=Avik|last=Roy|date=November 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Jose A.|last=DelReal|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2014/11/11/obamacare-consultant-under-fire-for-stupidity-of-the-american-voter-comment|title=Obamacare consultant under fire for 'stupidity of the American voter' comment|work=Washington Post|accessdate=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn two subsequent videos, Gruber was shown talking about the decision (which he attributed to [[John Kerry]]) to have the bill tax insurance companies instead of patients (the so-called \"Cadillac tax\"), which he called fundamentally the same thing economically but more palatable politically. In one video, he stated that \"the American people are too stupid to understand the difference\" between the two approaches, while in the other he said that the switch worked due to \"the lack of economic understanding of the American voter\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Obamacare: Voters, are you stupid?|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/11/14/politics/obamacare-voters-stupid-explainer|work=[[CNN]]|first=Jeremy|last=Diamond|date=November 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn another video, taken in 2010, Gruber expressed doubts that the ACA would significantly reduce health care costs, although he noted that lowering costs played a major part in the way the legislation had been promoted.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obamacare architect discussed misleading public in 4th newly uncovered video|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/11/13/politics/tapper-gruber|work=CNN|first=Jake|last=Tapper|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref> In another video, taken in 2011, Gruber again talks about manipulation behind the \"Cadillac tax\", this time also stating that the tax is designed so that, though it begins by affecting only 8% of insurance plans, it will \"over the next 20 years\" come to apply to nearly all employer-provided health plans.<ref name=\"obama promised\">{{cite news|title=Obama promised Obamacare wouldn't do exactly what Gruber says it will do|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/11/18/politics/gruber-obamacare-promises|work=[[CNN]]|first=Jake|last=Tapper|date=November 19, 2014}}</ref> Journalist [[Jake Tapper]] noted that Gruber's description of the \"Cadillac tax\" directly contradicted a promise that Obama had made before the bill was passed.<ref name=\"obama promised\"/>\n\nAfter the first of these videos came out, Gruber apologized and conceded he \"spoke inappropriately\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Jonathan Gruber to MSNBC: My 'Stupidity of the American Voter' Remark was Inappropriate|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/jonathan-gruber-to-msnbc-my-stupidity-of-the-american-voter-remark-was-inappropriate|work=Mediaite|first=Eddie|last=Scarry|date=November 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSome defenders of the ACA, such as [[Jonathan Cohn]], called Gruber's statements about Americans \"wrong and inappropriate\" while maintaining that the trickery of which Gruber spoke was standard procedure in passing legislation in Washington, D.C., and thus not a cause for scandal.<ref>{{cite news|title=What Jon Gruber's Quotes Really Tell Us About Obamacare\u2014and American Politics|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/120311/jonathan-gruber-and-obamacare-what-his-quotes-really-tell-us|first=Jonathan|last=Cohn|work=The New Republic|date=November 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Obamacare Debate Was One of the Most Transparent in Recent Memory|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/120251/jonathan-gruber-obamacare-comments-get-aca-history-wrong|first=Brian|last=Beutler|work= [[The New Republic]]|date=November 12, 2014}}</ref> Opponents of the Act, on the other hand, were harsher in their criticism: ''[[National Review|National Review Online]]'' editor and conservative commentator [[Rich Lowry]] said the videos were emblematic of \"the progressive mind, which values complexity over simplicity, favors indirect taxes and impositions on the American public so their costs can be hidden, and has a dim view of the average American\",<ref>{{cite news|title=Thank You, Jonathan Gruber|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/392672/thank-you-jonathan-gruber-rich-lowry|work=National Review|first=Rich|last=Lowry|date=November 14, 2014}}</ref> while commentator [[Charles Krauthammer]] called the first video \"the ultimate vindication of the charge that Obamacare was sold on a pack of lies.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The Gruber Confession|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/392644/gruber-confession-charles-krauthammer|work=National Review|first=Charles|last=Krauthammer|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nConservative [[S.E. Cupp]] wrote that the videos showed \"willful ignorance\" on Gruber's part in thinking that the Act was successfully marketed to voters, stating that \"the law has never cracked a 51% favorability rating\" and that, in the [[United States elections, 2010|first elections after the ACA passed]], Republicans, who had opposed it, retook the [[U.S. House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] and gained control of 11 additional state governorships.<ref>{{cite news|title=The guy who thinks voters are 'stupid'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/11/13/opinion/cupp-gruber-obamacare|first=S.E.|last=Cupp|work=CNN|date=November 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Nancy Pelosi]], then-Speaker of the House, who successfully shepherded the legislation through the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]], without a single GOP vote and despite some opposition from pro-life Democrats, stated in a press conference after the Gruber controversy, ''\"So I don't know who he is. He didn't help write our bill\"'', a comment [[PolitiFact]] described as \"inaccurate\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2014/nov/13/nancy-pelosi/nancy-pelosi-says-she-doesnt-know-who-jonathan-gru |title=Nancy Pelosi says she doesn't know who Jonathan Gruber is |website=PolitiFact.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Martosko |first=David |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2833632/Pelosi-disowns-Obamacare-architect-Jonathan-Gruber-stupidity-American-voter-video.html |title=Nancy Pelosi disowns Obamacare 'architect' Jonathan Gruber over video |website=Dailymail.co.uk |date=2014-11-13 |accessdate=2016-11-11}}</ref>\n\n====Congressional hearing====\nIn the wake of the controversy, Jonathan Gruber was called to testify before members of [[United States Congress]]. He gave testimony on December 9, 2014, in which he apologized for his remarks, which he called \"glib, thoughtless, and sometimes downright insulting\".<ref name=GruberTestimonyGowdyQuestion>{{cite AV media | people=Gruber, Jonathan| date=9 December 2014|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gnXzJm1sJRM| title=Rep. Trey Gowdy questions Jonathan Gruber (C SPAN) |location=Washington, DC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=MIT professor apologizes for health care law remarks|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2014/12/09/mit-professor-jonathan-gruber-apologizes-congress-for-remarks-about-stupidity-american-voter/AlrfLb2yWKWNTL9OvSaPFJ/story.html|work=Boston Globe|first=Noah|last=Bierman|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', in an editorial, called Gruber's apology unpersuasive, saying that \"his response to substantive questions suggested that he is mainly sorry for getting caught on tape\".<ref name=\"wallstreetjournal\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/forrest-gump-ph-d-1418171139|work= Wall Street Journal|title=Forrest Gump, PhD|date=December 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Effect on Vermont single-payer plan====\nOn December 17, 2014, [[Governor of Vermont|Vermont Governor]] [[Peter Shumlin]] cancelled the [[Vermont health care reform]] plan, on which Gruber had served as a consultant.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vermont bails on single-payer health care|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/12/vermont-peter-shumlin-single-payer-health-care-113653.html|first=Sarah|last=Wheaton|work=Politico|date=December 17, 2014}}</ref> Although budgetary concerns were cited as the reason for the cancellation, some called Gruber's involvement with the plan a factor as well.<ref>{{cite news |title=How Math, Lawsuits, and Jonathan Gruber Killed Vermont's Single-Payer Health Care Dream|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2014-12-18/how-math-lawsuits-and-jonathan-gruber-killed-vermonts-singlepayer-health-care-dream|first=David|last=Weigel|work=Bloomberg|date=December 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Vermont Public Radio|VPR]], Vermont state auditor Doug Hoffer is auditing Gruber's contracts<ref>{{cite news|title=Auditor: Invoices unsupported from Vt.health \"expert\"|url=http://www.burlingtonfreepress.com/story/news/politics/2015/01/23/vt-deal-health-expert-gruber-scrutiny/22222125|first=Dave|last=Gram|work=[[Burlington Free Press]]|date=January 24, 2015}}</ref> for [[Vermont health care reform]], which Gruber \"helped Vermont design\".<ref>{{cite news|title=State's Contract With Economist Jonathan Gruber Under Scrutiny|url=http://digital.vpr.net/post/states-contract-economist-jonathan-gruber-under-scrutiny|first=Peter|last=Hirschfeld|work=VPR|date=January 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Extent of contributions===\nThe extent of Gruber's contributions to both Massachusetts and federal health care reform has been the source of significant controversy. In 2014, the Obama administration claimed that Gruber did not have a major role in creating the ACA.<ref name=\"SArmourWSJ06212015\">{{cite news|last=Armour|first=Stephanie|date=June 21, 2015|title=MIT Economist Jonathan Gruber Had Bigger Role in Health Law, Emails Show|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/mit-economist-jonathan-gruber-had-bigger-role-in-health-law-emails-show-1434910195?KEYWORDS=Jonathan+Gruber|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]|location=[[New York City|New York]]|accessdate=June 22, 2015|quote=Jonathan Gruber, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology economist whose comments about the health-care law touched off a political furor, worked more closely than previously known with the White House and top federal officials to shape the law, previously unreleased emails show.}}</ref>\n\nAccording to emails released by the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|U.S. House Oversight Committee]] to the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', Gruber met and consulted with various Obama administration officials in charge of writing and developing the law,<ref name=\"SArmourWSJ06212015\"/> including [[Peter R. Orszag|Peter Orszag]], who was director of the [[Office of Management and Budget]] (OMB), [[Jason Furman]], an economic adviser to the president, [[Ezekiel Emanuel]], who was then a special adviser for health policy at OMB, [[Jeanne Lambrew]], a top Obama administration health adviser who worked at HHS and the White House, and [[Lawrence Summers]], then a top economic adviser in the administration.<ref name=\"SArmourWSJ06212015\"/> In July 2009, he was invited to meet personally with Obama.<ref name=\"SArmourWSJ06212015\"/>\n\nDuring his December 2014 congressional hearing, in both his written and oral testimony,<ref>{{cite news|title=Written Testimony of Professor Jonathan Gruber before the Committee on Oversight and Government Reform, U.S. House of Representatives|url=http://oversight.house.gov/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Gruber-Statement-12-9-ObamaCare1.pdf|work=United States Congress|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref> Gruber downplayed his own influence on the Massachusetts and national health care plans, stating: \"I did not draft Governor Romney\u2019s health care plan, and I was not the 'architect' of President Obama\u2019s health care plan.\" The newspaper ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' called this a contradiction of various statements that Gruber had previously made, claiming that at \"numerous speeches, lectures and TV interviews in the past four years, Gruber has been introduced as the 'architect' of the Massachusetts law and/or Obamacare\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Gruber on ObamaCare: 'I helped write it'|url=http://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/226626-jonathan-gruber-on-obamacare-i-helped-write-it|first=Jesse|last=Byrnes|work=The Hill|date=December 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://economics.mit.edu/files/9877 CV of Jonathan Gruber]\n* [https://www.nber.org/authors/jonathan_gruber [[National Bureau of Economic Research]] Publications by Jonathan Gruber]\n* [http://econ-www.mit.edu/faculty/gruberj/ MIT Faculty Profile - Jonathan Gruber]\n\n{{Fellows of the Econometric Society elected in 2016}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gruber, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American economists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American economists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Econometric Society]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Health economists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "the work's name is \"The New York Times\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonathan_Gruber_(economist)"}
{"title_page": "Pen railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox Station \n| name          = Pen\n| type          = \n| style         = \n| image         = Pein Railway station.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| image_caption = \n| address       = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|18.7354|73.0867|type:railwaystation_region:IN|display=inline}}\n| line          = [[Panvel railway station|Panvel]] - [[Roha railway station|Roha]] line\n| other         = \n| structure     = At grade\n| platform      = 3 \n| depth         = \n| levels        = \n| tracks        = \n| parking       = \n| bicycle       = \n| baggage_check = \n| opened        = \n| closed        = \n| rebuilt       = \n| electrified   = Yes\n| ADA           = \n| code          = PEN\n| owned         = [[Indian Railway]]\n| zone          = [[Central Railway (India)|Central Railway]]\n| former        = \n| passengers    = \n| pass_year     = \n| pass_percent  = \n| pass_system   = \n| mpassengers   = \n| services      = {{s-rail|title=Mumbai Suburban Railway}}\n{{s-line|system=Mumbai Suburban Railway|line=Vasai Road-Roha |branch=Vasai Road-Roha line |previous=Hamrapur|next=Kasu}}\n| map_type      = India#Maharashtra\n| map_dot_label = Pen\n| route_map     = {{MSR Central line|inline=1}}\n| map_state     = collapsed\n}}\n\n'''Pen railway station''' is a railway station on the [[Panvel railway station|Panvel]] - [[Roha]] route of [[Central Railway (India)|Central Railway]] in India. It is at a distance of 103.59&nbsp;km from [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus]] via [[Diva railway station|Diva]] junction. Its station code is PEN. It belongs to the Mumbai division of Central Railway.<ref name=\"CentralRailway-20100401\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cr.indianrailways.gov.in/cris/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,6,1191,1192,1394,1397|title=Central Railway Mumbai Division System Map|date=2010-04-01|publisher=[[Central Railway (India)|Central Railway]]|accessdate=4 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe station is situated in [[Raigad district]] of [[Maharashtra]]. It is situated between [[Hamrapur railway station|Hamrapur]] and [[Kasu railway station|Kasu]] railway stations. Two [[MEMU|MEMUs]] originate from here and terminate at [[Diva Junction railway station|Diva Junction]] and vice-versa. In addition to this, MEMUs from [[Roha railway station|Roha]] to Diva and vice versa halts here. Also, [[Dadar Central\u2013Ratnagiri Passenger|Dadar\u2013Ratnagiri Passenger]] and [[Sindhudurg Passenger|Diva\u2013Sindhudurg Passenger]] also has a halt here. These trains are being utilized completely by the local people but still there is a long pending demand to start [[Electric multiple unit|Local trains]] on this route both slow and fast services, for the convenience of the passengers. It'll also facilitate office-goers who goes to [[South Mumbai|SoBo]] or [[Mumbai Suburban|Mumbai Suburbs]] on a regular basis. \n\nThere's a goods train's line bifurcating from main line and goes to a factory in [[Alibag]]. There's a recent plan to introduce passenger train services on this route, thereby reducing travel time of the office-goers as Pen has direct passenger train services to [[Thane railway station|Thane]] and [[Dadar railway station|Dadar]]. At present one needs to take an ST (State Transport) bus to Pen and then take a train or ST bus to [[Panvel]], from where they can easily board the [[Electric multiple unit|Local trains]] to [[Mumbai]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=\u2018Central Rly to be completely electrified\u2019 |url=http://www.asianage.com/metros/mumbai/121118/central-rly-to-be-completely-electrified.html |website=The Asian Age |accessdate=8 March 2019 |date=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Raigad district]]\n{{Mumbai - Suburban Railway, Central}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox Station \n| name          = Pen\n| type          = \n| style         = \n| image         = Pein Railway station.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| image_caption = \n| address       = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|18.7354|73.0867|type:railwaystation_region:IN|display=inline}}\n| line          = [[Panvel railway station|Panvel]] - [[Roha railway station|Roha]] line\n| other         = \n| structure     = At grade\n| platform      = 3 \n| depth         = \n| levels        = \n| tracks        = \n| parking       = \n| bicycle       = \n| baggage_check = \n| opened        = \n| closed        = \n| rebuilt       = \n| electrified   = Yes\n| ADA           = \n| code          = PEN\n| owned         = [[Indian Railway]]\n| zone          = [[Central Railway (India)|Central Railway]]\n| former        = \n| passengers    = \n| pass_year     = \n| pass_percent  = \n| pass_system   = \n| mpassengers   = \n| services      = {{s-rail|title=Mumbai Suburban Railway}}\n{{s-line|system=Mumbai Suburban Railway|line=Vasai Road-Roha |branch=Vasai Road-Roha line |previous=Hamrapur|next=Kasu}}\n| map_type      = India#Maharashtra\n| map_dot_label = Pen\n| route_map     = {{MSR Central line|inline=1}}\n| map_state     = collapsed\n}}\n\n'''Pen railway station''' is a railway station on the [[Panvel railway station|Panvel]] - [[Roha]] route of [[Central Railway (India)|Central Railway]] in India. It is at a distance of 103.59&nbsp;km from [[Chhatrapati Shivaji Terminus]] via [[Diva railway station|Diva]] junction. Its station code is PEN. It belongs to the Mumbai division of Central Railway.<ref name=\"CentralRailway-20100401\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cr.indianrailways.gov.in/cris/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,6,1191,1192,1394,1397|title=Central Railway Mumbai Division System Map|date=2010-04-01|publisher=[[Central Railway (India)|Central Railway]]|accessdate=4 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe station is situated in [[Raigad district]] of [[Maharashtra]]. It is situated between [[Hamrapur railway station|Hamrapur]] and [[Kasu railway station|Kasu]] railway stations. Two [[MEMU|MEMUs]] originate from here and terminate at [[Diva Junction railway station|Diva Junction]] and vice-versa. In addition to this, MEMUs from [[Roha railway station|Roha]] to Diva and vice versa halts here. Also, [[Dadar Central\u2013Ratnagiri Passenger|Dadar\u2013Ratnagiri Passenger]] and [[Sindhudurg Passenger|Diva\u2013Sindhudurg Passenger]] also has a halt here. These trains are being utilized completely by the local people but still there is a long pending demand to start [[EMU|Local trains]] on this route both slow and fast services, for the convenience of the passengers. It'll also facilitate office-goers who goes to [[South Mumbai|SoBo]] or [[Mumbai Suburban|Mumbai Suburbs]] on a regular basis. \n\nThere's a goods train's line bifurcating from main line and goes to a factory in [[Alibag]]. There's a recent plan to introduce passenger train services on this route, thereby reducing travel time of the office-goers as Pen has direct passenger train services to [[Thane railway station|Thane]] and [[Dadar railway station|Dadar]]. At present one needs to take an ST (State Transport) bus to Pen and then take a train or ST bus to [[Panvel]], from where they can easily board the [[EMU|Local trains]] to [[Mumbai]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=\u2018Central Rly to be completely electrified\u2019 |url=http://www.asianage.com/metros/mumbai/121118/central-rly-to-be-completely-electrified.html |website=The Asian Age |accessdate=8 March 2019 |date=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Raigad district]]\n{{Mumbai - Suburban Railway, Central}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toEMU(link changed toElectric multiple unit; link changed toElectric multiple unit) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pen_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Dalea searlsiae", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{taxobox\n|name = Searls' Prairie clover\n|image = Dalea searlsiae 3.jpg\n| status = G4\n| status_system = TNC\n|regnum = [[Plant]]ae\n|divisio = [[Angiosperms]]\n|classis = [[Eudicots]]\n|unranked_ordo = [[Rosids]]\n|ordo = [[Fabales]]\n|familia = [[Fabaceae]]\n|genus = ''[[Dalea]]''\n|species = '''''D. searlsiae'''''\n|binomial = ''Dalea searlsiae''\n|binomial_authority = ([[Asa Gray|Gray]]) [[Rupert Charles Barneby|Barneby]]\n|}}\n\n'''''Dalea searlsiae''''', commonly known as '''Searls' prairie clover''', is a [[perennial plant|perennial]] [[legume]] species belonging to the ''[[Dalea]]'' genus.<ref name=calflora>[http://www.calflora.org/cgi-bin/species_query.cgi?where-taxon=Dalea+searlsiae  Calflora: ''Dalea searlsiae'']</ref><ref>Stewart, Jon Mark. ''Mojave Desert Wildflowers'', 1998, pg. 140.</ref> The species is found through arid regions of the southwestern [[United States]] and can survive in low moisture conditions. The species forms symbiotic relationships with [[nitrogen-fixing bacteria]] that can improve soil nutrient levels. Its large [[inflorescence]] attracts many species of [[Pollinator|pollinators]], and it lacks [[Toxin|toxins]] found in similar legume species. \u00a0As a result, the species has been considered for use in [[rangeland]] [[Land restoration|restoration]] and [[revegetation]] projects.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bushman, Johnson, Connors, and Jones|first=|date=2015|title=Germination and Seedling Emergence of Three Semiarid Western North American Legumes.|url=|journal=Rangeland Ecology and Management|volume=68|pages=501-506|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Gucker and Shaw|first=|title=Western Forbs: Biology, Ecology, and Use in Restoration. Searls\u2019 Prairie Clover.|publisher=Online E-Book|year=2019|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://plants.usda.gov/core/profile?symbol=DASE3|title=Dalea searlsiae|last=|first=|date=|website=USDA Plant Inventory|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Bhattarai, Bushman, Johnson, and Carman|first=|date=2011|title=Searls prairie clover (Dalea searlsiae) for rangeland revegetation: Phenotypic and genetic evaluations|url=|journal=Crop Science|volume=2|pages=716-727|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Taxonomy & Phylogeny ==\n\n=== Etymology ===\nSelf-taught British [[Botany|botanist]] [[Rupert Charles Barneby]] formally named the species and is responsible for characterizing much of the [[Endemism|endemic]] [[New World|new world]] legume species. The species was named after 19-year-old botanist Fanny Searls. She was the first to collect a specimen of this species in 1871.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=McMohan and Hufford|first=|date=2004|title=Phylogeny of Amorpheae (Fabaceae : Papilionoideae)|url=|journal=American Journal of Botany|volume=91|pages=1219-1230|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Phylogeny & Evolutionary History ===\nSearls\u2019 prairie clover belongs to the ''Dalea'' genus consisting of American prairie clovers.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> ''Dalea'' species are ''not'' true [[Clover|clovers]] (genus ''Trifolium'') and are only found in the [[Americas]]. While both genera belong to the [[Fabaceae]] family, they are not immediately related<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\n''Dalea'' belong to the tribe [[Amorpheae]]. The [[Biogeography|biogeographical]] history of Amorpheae has resulted in a pan-American distribution. Recent [[Molecular phylogenetics|molecular analyses]] have revealed that the ''Dalea'' genus does not constitute a [[Monophyly|monophyletic]] [[clade]]. All ''Dalea'' species descended from a [[Common descent|common ancestor]], but members of the ''[[Marina (plant)|Marina]]'' (false prairie clovers) also fall into this clade. While ''Marina'' is a monophyletic group, it falls within the lineage of ''Dalea'', indicating the false prairie clovers are a diverged lineage within the prairie clovers. Hence, ''Marina'' and ''Dalea'' form a monophyletic lineage with ''[[Psorothamnus]]'' being the [[sister group]]. These three genera are collectively referred to as the Daleoids.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Distribution & Range==\n\n=== Geographical Distribution ===\nSearls\u2019 prairie clover is native to the southwestern United States. While the plant is rarer than many legume species, [[Metapopulation|metapopulations]] can be found in southeastern [[California]], [[Utah]], [[Nevada]], and [[Arizona]]. Little is known about their distribution south of [[Mexico\u2013United States border|US-Mexico border]]<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />. \n\n=== Habitat and Growing Conditions ===\n''D. searlsiae'' is typically found in [[Deserts and xeric shrublands|desert shrublands]] and forested [[Forest|woodlands]]. Among forested regions of the southwestern United States, it is abundant in [[pine]]-[[juniper]] forests and rarer in [[spruce]]-[[fir]] forests. They are capable of surviving in a wide variety of soil conditions ranging from [[clay]]-rich to [[Sand|sandy]] substrates to rocky flats<ref name=\":0\" />, however their biological fitness and yield declines in high clay<ref name=\":2\" />. They are most common in [[Limestone|lime]]-rich soils. ''D. searlsiae'', being an interior species, is found at [[Elevation|elevations]] ranging between 1000-2800m above sea level<ref name=\":0\" />. \n\n==Description==\n\n=== Life History & Morphology ===\nLike most ''Dalea'' species, Searls\u2019 prairie clover is a [[Perennial plant|perennial]] species due to its woody [[taproot]]. In spring, the plant regenerates numerous stems sourced from the taproot. Leaves are odd-pinnately [[Glossary of leaf morphology|compounded]] (consisting of typically 5 or 7 [[Leaflet (botany)|leaflets]], but can range from 3-11 depending on age and health), alternating, and [[deciduous]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Mature plants range from 25-60cm tall. [[Flower|Flowering]] occurs in early spring with seed production occurring by early July. The plant forms tiny [[Plant reproductive morphology|perfect flowers]] clustered in a cylindrical spike. Each flower/pod has five [[stamen]], two [[Ovule|ovules]] per [[Pod (botany)|pod]], and only one seed matures per pod.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Variation & Selection ==\n\n=== Genetic & Phenotypic Variability ===\nThe Searls\u2019 prairie clover is a [[Ploidy|diploid]] organism with 14 [[Chromosome|chromosomes]] (2n = 14)<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. \u00a0Both [[genetic drift]] and [[gene flow]] are determinants of the local [[Population genetics|population structures]] of Searls\u2019 prairie clover. The species shows significant population-dependent variability in [[Phenotype|phenotypic]] characteristics<ref name=\":0\" />. \n\n=== Local Adaptation ===\nPhenotypic traits of the species vary with population and geographic location as a result of genetic and environmental factors.<ref name=\":2\" /> The average number of stems per plant can range from 6-23, the number of inflorescences can range from 8-46, and the average height ranges between 21-43cm.<ref name=\":2\" /> Bhattarai et al. (2011) used [[Principal component analysis|principle component analysis]] to correlate [[genotype]] to [[phenotype]] and found evidence of some [[Locus (genetics)|genetic loci]] being predictive of phenotype. Local Searls\u2019 prairie clover populations have undergone [[Evolutionary pressure|selective pressures]] leading to [[Local adaptation|local adaptations]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Ecology ==\nThe most of the [[ecology]] of Searls' prairie clover has been studied in relation to [[Symbiosis|symbioses]] and [[Herbivore|herbivory]].\n\n=== Rhizobial Symbiosis ===\nAs with most legumes, Searls\u2019 prairie clover forms symbiotic associations with [[Nitrogen fixation|nitrogen-fixing]] [[Rhizobia]] bacteria. This symbiosis improves soil [[nitrogen]] content and adds to the nutritional forage quality for herbivorous animals<ref name=\":0\" />. Commercial inoculant is available for ''D. searlsiae''<ref name=\":0\" />, but little research has been done to study the rhizobial-legume symbiosis of the species. \n\n=== Pollination ===\nWhile the species is capable of [[Self-pollination|self-pollinating]] in the absence of pollinators, it prefers to [[Pollination|cross-pollinate]] when possible. Pollination studies have shown self-pollination leads to a significantly reduced seed count with most seeds being inviable. Presence of Searls' prairie clover leads to a diverse pollinator [[community]] in the [[ecosystem]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Cane, Weber, and Miller|first=|date=2012|title=Breeding biologies, pollinators, and seed beetles of two prairie-clovers, Dalea ornata and Dalea searlsiae (Fabaceae: Amorpheae), from the intermountain West, USA|url=|journal=Western North American Naturalist|volume=72|pages=16-20|via=}}</ref>\n\n[[Bee]] species are the primary pollinator of ''D. searlsiae''. Twenty-two species of native bees have been identified as main pollinators of Searls' prairie clover. These include species of potter bees (''[[Anthidium]] spp.''), bumblebees (''[[Bumblebee|Bombus]] spp.''), plaster bees (''[[Colletes]] spp.''), and long-horned bees (''[[Eucera]]'' and ''[[Melissodes]]'' ''spp''.). In addition, various species of [[Wasp|wasps]], [[Fly|flies]], and [[Butterfly|butterflies]] are also important non-bee pollinators.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Herbivory ===\nCompared to other legumes, Searls\u2019 prairie clover is a suitable herbivore food source as it lacks toxic compounds. [[Sheep|Domestic sheep]] have shown a preference for the species. Consumption of Searls\u2019 prairie clover has been shown to be an excellent nutrient source, consisting of 17-20% [[Protein (nutrient)|crude protein]], and is hypothesized to prevent [[bloating]]. As a result, [[overgrazing]] has led to a reduction in the range and distribution of Searls\u2019 prairie clover.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Fire Tolerance ===\nGiven its habitat, it is likely Searls\u2019 prairie clover has evolved mechanisms to survive [[Wildfire|fire stress]]. Plants with destroyed or damaged stems often regenerate stems that are capable of flowering later in the growing season. Furthermore, the species has been found to occur following [[Controlled burn|controlled burnings]] indicating tolerance to fire.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Similar Species ==\nA newly identified species, ''[[Dalea janosensis]]'' collected from [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua, Mexico]] is morphologically similar to ''D. searlsiae''. Both species have rose-purple coloured flowers which can cause confusion. However, ''D. janosensis'' is significantly smaller than ''D. searlsiae'' with smaller leaves and non-deciduous bracts<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Estrada-C, Villarreal-Q, and Vega-M|first=|date=2014|title=A new species of Dalea series Compactae (Leguminosae: Amorpheae) from northwestern Chihuahua, Mexico|url=|journal=Brittonia|volume=66|pages=151-155|via=}}</ref>. \n\nWhen not flowering, ''D. searlsiae'' can be confused with ''[[Dalea cylindriceps|D. cylindriceps]]'', ''[[Dalea ornata|D. ornata]]'', and ''[[Dalea flavescens|D. flavescens]]''. However, flower colour can easily distinguish these species. Other morphological characteristics are often unreliable if used to distinguish these species due to [[phenotypic plasticity]]<ref name=\":5\" />.\n\n== Rangeland Restoration and Revegetation ==\nLegume species are in high demand for [[Revegetation|land revegetation]] and [[Land restoration|restoration]] efforts due to their symbiosis with [[Rhizobia|nitrogen-fixing Rhizobia]] bacteria. The presence of legumes alongside their rhizobial symbionts is desired in restoration, revegetation, and reclamation efforts to improve soil nutrient characteristics. However, the availability of these crops for these projects are limited due to the lack of cultivation. In 2011, Bhattarai and Bushman proposed the use of Searls' prairie clover in rangeland reclamation in the southwestern USA.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSearls\u2019 prairie clover is recommended for restoration and revegetation in regions attaining 152-356mm in [[Precipitation|annual precipitation]]. The rationale for using ''D. searlsiae'' in restoration projects is attributed to its rehabilitation of soil nutrient conditions and attraction of pollinators.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n=== Cultivation and Establishment of Seeds ===\nThree phenotypic/genetic [[Germplasm|germplasms]] identified by Bhattarai et al. (2011) are used in land revegetation and restoration efforts.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Johnson, Bushman, Connors, Bhattarai, Jones, Jensen, Parr, and Eldredge|first=|date=2015|title=Notice of release of Fanny Germplasm, Carmel Germplasm, and Bonneville Germplasm Searls\u2019 prairie clover: selected class of natural germplasm|url=|journal=Native Plants Journal|volume=16|pages=265-275|via=}}</ref> The \u2018Fanny\u2019 germplasm originates from seeds found at Patterson Pass in east-central [[Nevada]] and is recommended for [[USDA plant hardiness zone]] 5b. The \u2018Carmel\u2019 germplasm originates from the [[Colorado Plateau]] of south-central [[Utah]] and is recommended for USDA plant hardiness zone 7a. The Bonneville germplasm was sourced from NW Utah near the Nevada border in USDA plant hardiness zone 6b. However, the Bonneville germplasm was found to be a genetically distinct population and is recommended for use in northwestern Utah. Local germplasms are recommended to prevent outbreeding depression.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> \n\nThe three germplasms were made available by the [[Agricultural Research Service|USDA\u2019s Agricultural Research Service]] for revegetation and restoration efforts. In 2015, researchers collected seeds from the regions identified by Bhattarai et al. (2011), created germplasms for future cultivation, and verified the genotype of each germplasm through genetic testing.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nPlanting seeds for these efforts requires pre-treatments. Allowing seeds to overwinter after planting in fall is an effective method. However, many projects use a 5-minute treatment with 98% [[sulfuric acid]] to increase germination success.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe species can grow well without irrigation. However, in drier years, irrigation of 100-200mm can be beneficial to increase yield.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shock, Feibert, Rivera, Saunders, Shaw, and Kilkenny|first=|date=2018|title=Irrigation requirements for seed production of three leguminous wildflowers of the U.S. Intermountain West|url=|journal=HortScience|volume=53|pages=692-697|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Antimicrobial and Insecticidal Properties ==\n[[Chromatography|Chromatographic fractionation]] studies on ''D. searlsiae'' root extracts have identified at least six root compounds that infer [[antimicrobial]] activity. Among these, two known [[Flavanone|flavanones]] and four newly discovered flavanones displayed antimicrobial activity against ''[[Streptococcus]],'' ''[[Bacillus]],'' and ''[[Staphylococcus]]'' bacteria.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Belofsky, Foss, Diamond, Santana, Darley, Dowd, Coleman, and Ferreira|first=|date=2014|title=Antimicrobial and antiinsectan phenolic metabolites of Dalea searlsiae|url=|journal=Journal of Natural Products|volume=77|pages=1140-1149|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe root also contains two [[Rotenoid|rotenoids]] and one flavanone that displayed strong [[Insecticide|insecticidal]] activity. It remains to be determined how these compounds enhance the [[Fitness (biology)|fitness]] of the plant.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* ''[[Dalea]]''\n* [[Dalea ornata|''Dalea ornata'']]\n* [[Dalea purpurea|''Dalea purpurea'']]\n* [[Amorpheae]]\n* [[Fabaceae]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.calflora.org/cgi-bin/species_query.cgi?where-taxon=Dalea+searlsiae  Calflora Database: ''Dalea searlsiae'' (Searls' prairie clover)]\n*[http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/eflora/eflora_display.php?tid=22288  Jepson Manual eFlora (TJM2) treatment]\n*[http://plants.usda.gov/java/profile?symbol=DASE3 USDA Plants Profile for ''Dalea searlsiae'' (Searls' prairie clover)]\n*[http://calphotos.berkeley.edu/cgi/img_query?query_src=photos_index&where-taxon=Dalea+searlsiae U.C. Photos gallery]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5210723}}\n\n[[Category:Dalea|searlsiae]]\n[[Category:Flora of the California desert regions]]\n[[Category:Flora of Nevada]]\n[[Category:Flora of Utah]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Great Basin]]\n[[Category:Natural history of the Mojave Desert]]\n[[Category:North American desert flora]]\n[[Category:Inyo Mountains]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{taxobox\n|name = Searls' Prairie clover\n|image = Dalea searlsiae 3.jpg\n| status = G4\n| status_system = TNC\n|regnum = [[Plant]]ae\n|divisio = [[Angiosperms]]\n|classis = [[Eudicots]]\n|unranked_ordo = [[Rosids]]\n|ordo = [[Fabales]]\n|familia = [[Fabaceae]]\n|genus = ''[[Dalea]]''\n|species = '''''D. searlsiae'''''\n|binomial = ''Dalea searlsiae''\n|binomial_authority = ([[Asa Gray|Gray]]) [[Rupert Charles Barneby|Barneby]]\n|}}\n\n'''''Dalea searlsiae''''', commonly known as '''Searls' prairie clover''', is a [[perennial plant|perennial]] [[legume]] species belonging to the ''[[Dalea]]'' genus.<ref name=calflora>[http://www.calflora.org/cgi-bin/species_query.cgi?where-taxon=Dalea+searlsiae  Calflora: ''Dalea searlsiae'']</ref><ref>Stewart, Jon Mark. ''Mojave Desert Wildflowers'', 1998, pg. 140.</ref> The species is found through arid regions of the southwestern [[United States]] and can survive in low moisture conditions. The species forms symbiotic relationships with [[nitrogen-fixing bacteria]] that can improve soil nutrient levels. Its large [[inflorescence]] attracts many species of [[Pollinator|pollinators]], and it lacks [[Toxin|toxins]] found in similar legume species. \u00a0As a result, the species has been considered for use in [[rangeland]] [[Land restoration|restoration]] and [[revegetation]] projects.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bushman, Johnson, Connors, and Jones|first=|date=2015|title=Germination and Seedling Emergence of Three Semiarid Western North American Legumes.|url=|journal=Rangeland Ecology and Management|volume=68|pages=501-506|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Gucker and Shaw|first=|title=Western Forbs: Biology, Ecology, and Use in Restoration. Searls\u2019 Prairie Clover.|publisher=Online E-Book|year=2019|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://plants.usda.gov/core/profile?symbol=DASE3|title=Dalea searlsiae|last=|first=|date=|website=USDA Plant Inventory|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Bhattarai, Bushman, Johnson, and Carman|first=|date=2011|title=Searls prairie clover (Dalea searlsiae) for rangeland revegetation: Phenotypic and genetic evaluations|url=|journal=Crop Science|volume=2|pages=716-727|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Taxonomy & Phylogeny ==\n\n=== Etymology ===\nSelf-taught British [[Botany|botanist]] [[Rupert Charles Barneby]] formally named the species and is responsible for characterizing much of the [[Endemism|endemic]] [[New World|new world]] legume species. The species was named after 19-year-old botanist Fanny Searls. She was the first to collect a specimen of this species in 1871.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=McMohan and Hufford|first=|date=2004|title=Phylogeny of Amorpheae (Fabaceae : Papilionoideae)|url=|journal=American Journal of Botany|volume=91|pages=1219-1230|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Phylogeny & Evolutionary History ===\nSearls\u2019 prairie clover belongs to the ''Dalea'' genus consisting of American prairie clovers.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> ''Dalea'' species are ''not'' true [[Clover|clovers]] (genus ''Trifolium'') and are only found in the [[Americas]]. While both genera belong to the [[Fabaceae]] family, they are not immediately related<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\n''Dalea'' belong to the tribe [[Amorpheae]]. The [[Biogeography|biogeographical]] history of Amorpheae has resulted in a pan-American distribution. Recent [[Molecular phylogenetics|molecular analyses]] have revealed that the ''Dalea'' genus does not constitute a [[Monophyly|monophyletic]] [[clade]]. All ''Dalea'' species descended from a [[Common descent|common ancestor]], but members of the ''[[Marina (plant)|Marina]]'' (false prairie clovers) also fall into this clade. While ''Marina'' is a monophyletic group, it falls within the lineage of ''Dalea'', indicating the false prairie clovers are a diverged lineage within the prairie clovers. Hence, ''Marina'' and ''Dalea'' form a monophyletic lineage with ''[[Psorothamnus]]'' being the [[sister group]]. These three genera are collectively referred to as the Daleoids.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Distribution & Range==\n\n=== Geographical Distribution ===\nSearls\u2019 prairie clover is native to the southwestern United States. While the plant is rarer than many legume species, [[Metapopulation|metapopulations]] can be found in southeastern [[California]], [[Utah]], [[Nevada]], and [[Arizona]]. Little is known about their distribution south of [[Mexico\u2013United States border|US-Mexico border]]<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />. \n\n=== Habitat and Growing Conditions ===\n''D. searlsiae'' is typically found in [[Deserts and xeric shrublands|desert shrublands]] and forested [[Forest|woodlands]]. Among forested regions of the southwestern United States, it is abundant in [[pine]]-[[juniper]] forests and rarer in [[spruce]]-[[fir]] forests. They are capable of surviving in a wide variety of soil conditions ranging from [[clay]]-rich to [[Sand|sandy]] substrates to rocky flats<ref name=\":0\" />, however their biological fitness and yield declines in high clay<ref name=\":2\" />. They are most common in [[Limestone|lime]]-rich soils. ''D. searlsiae'', being an interior species, is found at [[Elevation|elevations]] ranging between 1000-2800m above sea level<ref name=\":0\" />. \n\n==Description==\n\n=== Life History & Morphology ===\nLike most ''Dalea'' species, Searls\u2019 prairie clover is a [[Perennial plant|perennial]] species due to its woody [[taproot]]. In spring, the plant regenerates numerous stems sourced from the taproot. Leaves are odd-pinnately [[Glossary of leaf morphology|compounded]] (consisting of typically 5 or 7 [[Leaflet (botany)|leaflets]], but can range from 3-11 depending on age and health), alternating, and [[deciduous]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Mature plants range from 25-60cm tall. [[Flower|Flowering]] occurs in early spring with seed production occurring by early July. The plant forms tiny [[Plant reproductive morphology|perfect flowers]] clustered in a cylindrical spike. Each flower/pod has five [[stamen]], two [[Ovule|ovules]] per [[Pod (botany)|pod]], and only one seed matures per pod.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Variation & Selection ==\n\n=== Genetic & Phenotypic Variability ===\nThe Searls\u2019 prairie clover is a [[Ploidy|diploid]] organism with 14 [[Chromosome|chromosomes]] (2n = 14)<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />. \u00a0Both [[genetic drift]] and [[gene flow]] are determinants of the local [[Population genetics|population structures]] of Searls\u2019 prairie clover. The species shows significant population-dependent variability in [[Phenotype|phenotypic]] characteristics<ref name=\":0\" />. \n\n=== Local Adaptation ===\nPhenotypic traits of the species vary with population and geographic location as a result of genetic and environmental factors.<ref name=\":2\" /> The average number of stems per plant can range from 6-23, the number of inflorescences can range from 8-46, and the average height ranges between 21-43cm.<ref name=\":2\" /> Bhattarai et al. (2011) used [[Principal component analysis|principle component analysis]] to correlate [[genotype]] to [[phenotype]] and found evidence of some [[Locus (genetics)|genetic loci]] being predictive of phenotype. Local Searls\u2019 prairie clover populations have undergone [[Evolutionary pressure|selective pressures]] leading to [[Local adaptation|local adaptations]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Ecology ==\nThe most of the [[ecology]] of Searls' prairie clover has been studied in relation to [[Symbiosis|symbioses]] and [[Herbivore|herbivory]].\n\n=== Rhizobial Symbiosis ===\nAs with most legumes, Searls\u2019 prairie clover forms symbiotic associations with [[Nitrogen fixation|nitrogen-fixing]] [[Rhizobia]] bacteria. This symbiosis improves soil [[nitrogen]] content and adds to the nutritional forage quality for herbivorous animals<ref name=\":0\" />. Commercial inoculant is available for ''D. searlsiae''<ref name=\":0\" />, but little research has been done to study the rhizobial-legume symbiosis of the species. \n\n=== Pollination ===\nWhile the species is capable of [[Self-pollination|self-pollinating]] in the absence of pollinators, it prefers to [[Pollination|cross-pollinate]] when possible. Pollination studies have shown self-pollination leads to a significantly reduced seed count with most seeds being inviable. Presence of Searls' prairie clover leads to a diverse pollinator [[community]] in the [[ecosystem]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Cane, Weber, and Miller|first=|date=2012|title=Breeding biologies, pollinators, and seed beetles of two prairie-clovers, Dalea ornata and Dalea searlsiae (Fabaceae: Amorpheae), from the intermountain West, USA|url=|journal=Western North American Naturalist|volume=72|pages=16-20|via=}}</ref>\n\n[[Bee]] species are the primary pollinator of ''D. searlsiae''. Twenty-two species of native bees have been identified as main pollinators of Searls' prairie clover. These include species of potter bees (''[[Anthidium]] spp.''), bumblebees (''[[Bumblebee|Bombus]] spp.''), plaster bees (''[[Colletes]] spp.''), and long-horned bees (''[[Eucera]]'' and ''[[Melissodes]]'' ''spp''.). In addition, various species of [[Wasp|wasps]], [[Fly|flies]], and [[Butterfly|butterflies]] are also important non-bee pollinators.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Herbivory ===\nCompared to other legumes, Searls\u2019 prairie clover is a suitable herbivore food source as it lacks toxic compounds. [[Sheep|Domestic sheep]] have shown a preference for the species. Consumption of Searls\u2019 prairie clover has been shown to be an excellent nutrient source, consisting of 17-20% [[Protein (nutrient)|crude protein]], and is hypothesized to prevent [[bloating]]. As a result, [[overgrazing]] has led to a reduction in the range and distribution of Searls\u2019 prairie clover.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Fire Tolerance ===\nGiven its habitat, it is likely Searls\u2019 prairie clover has evolved mechanisms to survive [[Wildfire|fire stress]]. Plants with destroyed or damaged stems often regenerate stems that are capable of flowering later in the growing season. Furthermore, the species has been found to occur following [[Controlled burn|controlled burnings]] indicating tolerance to fire.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Similar Species ==\nA newly identified species, ''[[Dalea janosensis]]'' collected from [[Chihuahua, Mexico]] is morphologically similar to ''D. searlsiae''. Both species have rose-purple coloured flowers which can cause confusion. However, ''D. janosensis'' is significantly smaller than ''D. searlsiae'' with smaller leaves and non-deciduous bracts<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Estrada-C, Villarreal-Q, and Vega-M|first=|date=2014|title=A new species of Dalea series Compactae (Leguminosae: Amorpheae) from northwestern Chihuahua, Mexico|url=|journal=Brittonia|volume=66|pages=151-155|via=}}</ref>. \n\nWhen not flowering, ''D. searlsiae'' can be confused with ''[[Dalea cylindriceps|D. cylindriceps]]'', ''[[Dalea ornata|D. ornata]]'', and ''[[Dalea flavescens|D. flavescens]]''. However, flower colour can easily distinguish these species. Other morphological characteristics are often unreliable if used to distinguish these species due to [[phenotypic plasticity]]<ref name=\":5\" />.\n\n== Rangeland Restoration and Revegetation ==\nLegume species are in high demand for [[Revegetation|land revegetation]] and [[Land restoration|restoration]] efforts due to their symbiosis with [[Rhizobia|nitrogen-fixing Rhizobia]] bacteria. The presence of legumes alongside their rhizobial symbionts is desired in restoration, revegetation, and reclamation efforts to improve soil nutrient characteristics. However, the availability of these crops for these projects are limited due to the lack of cultivation. In 2011, Bhattarai and Bushman proposed the use of Searls' prairie clover in rangeland reclamation in the southwestern USA.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSearls\u2019 prairie clover is recommended for restoration and revegetation in regions attaining 152-356mm in [[Precipitation|annual precipitation]]. The rationale for using ''D. searlsiae'' in restoration projects is attributed to its rehabilitation of soil nutrient conditions and attraction of pollinators.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n=== Cultivation and Establishment of Seeds ===\nThree phenotypic/genetic [[Germplasm|germplasms]] identified by Bhattarai et al. (2011) are used in land revegetation and restoration efforts.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Johnson, Bushman, Connors, Bhattarai, Jones, Jensen, Parr, and Eldredge|first=|date=2015|title=Notice of release of Fanny Germplasm, Carmel Germplasm, and Bonneville Germplasm Searls\u2019 prairie clover: selected class of natural germplasm|url=|journal=Native Plants Journal|volume=16|pages=265-275|via=}}</ref> The \u2018Fanny\u2019 germplasm originates from seeds found at Patterson Pass in east-central [[Nevada]] and is recommended for [[USDA plant hardiness zone]] 5b. The \u2018Carmel\u2019 germplasm originates from the [[Colorado Plateau]] of south-central [[Utah]] and is recommended for USDA plant hardiness zone 7a. The Bonneville germplasm was sourced from NW Utah near the Nevada border in USDA plant hardiness zone 6b. However, the Bonneville germplasm was found to be a genetically distinct population and is recommended for use in northwestern Utah. Local germplasms are recommended to prevent outbreeding depression.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> \n\nThe three germplasms were made available by the [[Agricultural Research Service|USDA\u2019s Agricultural Research Service]] for revegetation and restoration efforts. In 2015, researchers collected seeds from the regions identified by Bhattarai et al. (2011), created germplasms for future cultivation, and verified the genotype of each germplasm through genetic testing.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nPlanting seeds for these efforts requires pre-treatments. Allowing seeds to overwinter after planting in fall is an effective method. However, many projects use a 5-minute treatment with 98% [[sulfuric acid]] to increase germination success.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe species can grow well without irrigation. However, in drier years, irrigation of 100-200mm can be beneficial to increase yield.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shock, Feibert, Rivera, Saunders, Shaw, and Kilkenny|first=|date=2018|title=Irrigation requirements for seed production of three leguminous wildflowers of the U.S. Intermountain West|url=|journal=HortScience|volume=53|pages=692-697|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Antimicrobial and Insecticidal Properties ==\n[[Chromatography|Chromatographic fractionation]] studies on ''D. searlsiae'' root extracts have identified at least six root compounds that infer [[antimicrobial]] activity. Among these, two known [[Flavanone|flavanones]] and four newly discovered flavanones displayed antimicrobial activity against ''[[Streptococcus]],'' ''[[Bacillus]],'' and ''[[Staphylococcus]]'' bacteria.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Belofsky, Foss, Diamond, Santana, Darley, Dowd, Coleman, and Ferreira|first=|date=2014|title=Antimicrobial and antiinsectan phenolic metabolites of Dalea searlsiae|url=|journal=Journal of Natural Products|volume=77|pages=1140-1149|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe root also contains two [[Rotenoid|rotenoids]] and one flavanone that displayed strong [[Insecticide|insecticidal]] activity. It remains to be determined how these compounds enhance the [[Fitness (biology)|fitness]] of the plant.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== See Also ==\n\n* ''[[Dalea]]''\n* [[Dalea ornata|''Dalea ornata'']]\n* [[Dalea purpurea|''Dalea purpurea'']]\n* [[Amorpheae]]\n* [[Fabaceae]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.calflora.org/cgi-bin/species_query.cgi?where-taxon=Dalea+searlsiae  Calflora Database: ''Dalea searlsiae'' (Searls' prairie clover)]\n*[http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/eflora/eflora_display.php?tid=22288  Jepson Manual eFlora (TJM2) treatment]\n*[http://plants.usda.gov/java/profile?symbol=DASE3 USDA Plants Profile for ''Dalea searlsiae'' (Searls' prairie clover)]\n*[http://calphotos.berkeley.edu/cgi/img_query?query_src=photos_index&where-taxon=Dalea+searlsiae U.C. Photos gallery]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5210723}}\n\n[[Category:Dalea|searlsiae]]\n[[Category:Flora of the California desert regions]]\n[[Category:Flora of Nevada]]\n[[Category:Flora of Utah]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Great Basin]]\n[[Category:Natural history of the Mojave Desert]]\n[[Category:North American desert flora]]\n[[Category:Inyo Mountains]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toChihuahua(link changed toChihuahua (state)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dalea_searlsiae"}
